<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cash For Questions Tory MP Quits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 27 (Xinhua) -- The ruling Conservative party's
general election campaign suffered a serious blow last night with
the decision by one of its MPs Tim Smith to quit over his
involvement in the so-called "cash for questions" scandal.
</P>
<P>
Smith resigned in the wake of the Guardian newspaper's
publication last week of leaked extracts of his questioning during
a parliamentary investigation into MPs accepting cash for asking
questions in parliament.
</P>
<P>
Smith, a candidate for the safe Conservative seat of
Beaconsfield, claimed that he was the victim of a media witch hunt.
</P>
<P>
He said on Wednesday, "I very much regret that the action of
the Guardian newspaper in support of the Labor party has made my
course of action inevitable with its complete disregard for both
parliamentary privilege and natural justice."
</P>
<P>
Smith resigned as a minister in October 1994 after a series of
articles in the Guardian alleging he was paid to ask questions in
parliament on behalf of Egyptian businessman Mohammed al-Fayed,
owner of London's luxury Harrods store.
</P>
<P>
He admitted failing to declare 25,000 pounds (40,000
U.S. dollars) in cash payments from al-Fayed in the register of
MPs' outside earnings. But he remained as an MP, saying his
failure to declare was a mistake but not illegal.
</P>
<P>
A parliamentary committee was set up to investigate claims that
money was paid to Smith and former junior trade minister Neil
Hamilton and eight other MPs by a lobbyist.
</P>
<P>
But John Major's decision to dismiss parliament last Friday,
launching the longest election campaign in 80 years, meant the
report on these charges could not be published before the election.
</P>
<P>
The opposition Labor party, strong favorites to win the
election, accused Major of deliberately closing parliament to
cover up the scandal. But the prime minister rejected the charges.
</P>
<P>
There was strong speculation that Smith's decision to step down
as a candidate in the election had been pressed on him by party
bosses hoping him to damp down the damage being caused by a string
of sleaze scandals that have hit the Conservatives.
</P>
<P>
A colleague of the prime minister said Wednesday night
that Smith had to quit to "avoid damage to the PM."
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister John Major defended Smith, telling the Yorkshire
Post newspaper on Wednesday that " people are innocent until
proved guilty."
</P>
<P>
He also said that he wanted to see Smith and the nine other
Tory MPs under investigation by Sir Gordon re-elected on May 1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
