<HEADLINE> Albanian Parliamentary Chief Says Relations with Greece Good </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, March 27 (Xinhua) -- The chairman of Albania's
parliament Pjeter Arbnori said yesterday that friendly relations
between Albania and Greece would not falter.
</P>
<P>
Arbnori, speaking after a meeting of the National Assembly, was
responding to accusations by the former director of the National
Intelligence Bureau, Bashkim Gazidede, that Greece and the United
States were responsible for fomenting the current upheaval in
southern Albania.
</P>
<P>
Gazidede said during the assembly meeting that organizations
from Greece and the United States schemed to subvert the rule of
the Albanian government in Vorioepirn in southern Albania in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Though the plot failed at the time, it was resurrected and
carried out recently, he said.
</P>
<P>
His remarks triggered immediate denial and condemnations from
both Greece and the United States.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the Albanian Foreign Ministry described the
accusations as baseless.
</P>
<P>
The current crisis in Albania stemmed from the collapse of
fraudulent investment schemes in January in which thousands of
Albanians lost their life savings.
</P>
<P>
Weeks of street protests turned violent three weeks ago when
angry demonstrators looted military depots in the south of the
country and took control of several towns. 
</P>
</TEXT>
