<HEADLINE> Chinese, Bolivian Presidents Hold Talks (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 27 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese Government is ready
to work with the Bolivian Government to develop long-term, stable
and all-round friendship and cooperative ties with an eye to the
21st century.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang Zemin made this remark during his talks with
visiting Bolivian President Gonzalo Sanchez de Lozada here this
afternoon, where they had profound and fruitful discussions.
</P>
<P>
Jiang welcomed Sanchez on behalf of the Chinese Government and
people.
</P>
<P>
Sanchez expressed condolences over the death of Deng Xiaoping,
and praised the miracles made by the Chinese people in the
modernization drive.
</P>
<P>
"We will unsweringly take the path of building socialism with
Chinese characteristics, which was initiated by Deng." Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
Since China and Bolivia forged diplomatic ties in 1985, Jiang
said, Sino-Bolivian tie have been developing steadily with growing
exchanges in various fields and deepening mutual understanding and
friendship.
</P>
<P>
In international affairs, the two countries have supported each
other and conducted close cooperation, he said.
</P>
<P>
Jiang went on to note that the bilateral economic and
technologic cooperation is "satisfactory and fruitful." The
projects financed by Chinese credit have brought about high
economic returns and good social effect, and there is a strong
momentum for expanding bilateral trade, he added.
</P>
<P>
"Our two countries are trust-worthy friends, and we are
satisfied with the growth of bilateral relations." Jiang noted.
</P>
<P>
He said the Chinese Government attaches great importance to
enhancing the friendship and cooperation between the two peoples,
and is willing to work with the Bolivian Government toward this
end.
</P>
<P>
The Bolivian president said his China visit eloquently shows
that Bolivia is dedicated to long-term development of bilateral
ties and enhancement of bilateral friendship and cooperations.
</P>
<P>
Sanchez said his country pursues the "one China" policy and
will not forge any official ties with Taiwan, which drew Jiang's
appreciations.
</P>
<P>
The two heads of state agreed to strengthen mutually beneficial
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang described China and Bolivia as countries with
vast land and abundant resources, and said the two countries, with
strong economic complementarity, has great potentials to be tapped
in their cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Jiang pointed out the two sides can seek new ways to expand
exchanges in areas like mining, energy, agriculture, animal
husbandry, and forestry.
</P>
<P>
"China is willing to strengthen its trade and economic
cooperation with Bolivia on the principled basis of equality,
mutual benefit, effectiveness, diversity, and common growth,"
Jiang said.
</P>
</TEXT>
