<HEADLINE> S'pore to Gain Around 1 Billion US Dollars With </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Information
Technology (IT) exporters will stand to gain an accumulated
potential tariff savings of around one billion US dollars when the
Information Technology Agreement (ITA) is fully implemented, the
Singapore Trade Development Board (TDB) said today.
</P>
<P>
This figure represents a 50 percent rise over the previous
estimate, the TDB said, adding that the tariff savings were based
on Singapore's 1996 IT domestic exports to its major markets,
which included the United States, the European Union nations,
Japan, Hong Kong, Indonesia, Malaysia, and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Implementation of the ITA, which was agreed upon in December
1996 at the inaugural World Trade Organization (WTO) Ministerial
Conference in Singapore, will begin from July 1, 1997 according to
schedule. Tariffs on relevant IT products will then be
progressively reduced and eliminated by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The number of ITA participating members has now increased from
the original 28 to 39. The first 28 members under the ITA were
Australia, Canada, Chinese Taipei, the 15 European Union nations,
Hong Kong, Japan, South Korea, Indonesia, Iceland, Norway,
Singapore, Switzerland, Turkey, and the United States.
</P>
<P>
The additional 11 new members are New Zealand, Macao, Costa
Rica, Malaysia, Thailand, Romania, Estonia, Israel, India, the
Slovak Republic and the Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
Together, these participating members represent more than 92
percent of world trade in IT goods, the TDB said, adding that with
the 90 percent threshold having been exceeded, this in effect
signifies a broad acceptance of the ITA by major IT exporting
economies.
</P>
<P>
The ITA covers five main categories of products, namely
computers, telecommunication products, semiconductors,
semiconductor manufacturing equipment and scientific equipment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
