<HEADLINE> More Stringent Criteria to Be Applied on Noisy Hammers in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 27 (Xinhua) -- More stringent noise criteria
will be applied on noisy percussive hammers and such construction
tools are to be practically banned in built-up areas in Hong Kong,
 the Hong Kong government said here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A noise control bill approved here today seeks to reduce noise
level generated from percussive piling by phasing out the use of
three most noisy types -- diesel, pneumatic and steam -- in
built-up areas and replace them with quieter alternatives such as
the hydraulic ones.
</P>
<P>
A government spokesman said that percussive piling generates
significant noise impact on its neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
Of the three types, diesel hammer accounts for over 80 percent
of piling permits issued and produces noise levels up to 103 dB
(A) at 10 meters. Pneumatic and steam hammer also produces noise
level up to 106 dB (A) at 10 meters.
</P>
<P>
By comparison, hydraulic hammer is more environmentally
friendly as it produces about two to nine dB (A), quieter than
diesel, pneumatic and steam hammers under the same site conditions
 and will not emit filthy smoke.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, mitigation measures such as acoustic shrouds may be
applied to further reduce noise.
</P>
<P>
In collaboration with government departments, the Hong Kong
Construction Association has completed a series of piling tests
which found that hydraulic hammers can achieve the required hammer
 efficiency.
</P>
<P>
And to moderate the impact on the construction industry and to
allow time for suppliers of hydraulic hammers to meet the demand,
it was proposed to phase out noisy hammers in four stages at
six-month intervals beginning in early 1998.
</P>
<P>
Progressively, the noise criteria for issuing constructing
noise permits to percussive piling operations using those hammers
will be tightened, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
During the final stage at around year 2000 the use of noisy
hammers in built-up areas will practically be banned. Nonetheless,
they can still be used in remote areas where they will not
disturb anyone, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
