<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Tourist Arrivals on Rise in January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's tourism industry is
 off to a good start in 1997 with a substantial 12.3 percent
increase in visitor arrivals in January this year, according to
the latest statistics released today by the Hong Kong Tourist
Association (HKTA).
</P>
<P>
This rise means that almost 988,300 visitors came to Hong Kong
in the first month of the historic year, an HKTA spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The majority of major market regions recorded good growth in
January. Arrivals from Taiwan showed the highest increase, with a
rise of 43.1 percent to almost 161,350, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Visitors from the Chinese mainland were up by 21.4 percent to
over 221,750, arrivals from North Asia rose by 9.8 percent to more
 than 246,600, while those from Australia, New Zealand and the
South Pacific increased by 9.5 percent to over 39,100.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Hong Kong set a new record in arrivals, with a total
 of 11.7 million visitors for the year.
</P>
<P>
The HKTA is forecasting an increase of about 7 percent over
that total for year-end 1997 figures, about 12.5 million visitors
this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
