<DOCNO> XIE19970328.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak PM to Announce Relief-Oriented Mini-Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif will announce the first ever relief-oriented "Mini Budget"
soon, with downward revision in the income tax, tariff rates and
sales tax besides a unique industrial package.
</P>
<P>
The Economic Revival Program will provide incentives and
concessions across the board to almost each sector of the economy
in a direct and indirect manner.
</P>
<P>
The budgetary package, three months ahead of the new fiscal
year (1997-98), is expected to ensure a diminishing trend in the
price spiral, arresting a surge in inflationary pressure, contrary
to the previous budgetary proposals which had always entailed an
upward trend in the prices.
</P>
<P>
The recommendations of the different committees constituted by
the prime minister will provide a basis for the Economic Revival
Program containing a substantial reforms package, ensuring rapid
economic development and relief to the common man.
</P>
<P>
Despite reduction in the tax and tariff rates, an increase in
revenue collection is expected by broadening the tax base.
Rationalization of tax rates will not only net new tax payers but
will also check tax evasion.
</P>
<P>
Government sources have expressed the hope that both
individuals and companies are most likely to benefit from the
rationalization of tax rates.
</P>
<P>
The concessions and relief, in fact, are aimed at lessening
unbearable burdens on the tax payers, improving the revenue
collection and minimizing tax evasion, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
A substantial industrial package to be appended with overall
budgetary proposals and economic revival program is expected to
provide an impetus in accelerating the pace of industrial
production and augmenting the country's exports, thus slashing the
trade deficit, presently around 4.5 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Foreign as well as local investors will be provided special
industrial zones with a variety of incentives and concessions to
improve productivity and production in traditional as well as
non-conventional sectors of the economy, according to the sources.
</P>
<P>
Another package for the revival of closed and sick units will
also be unfolded to bring them into the mainstream of the economy,
enabling them to contribute towards economic growth in a phased
manner.
</P>
<P>
The Economic Revival Program will also envisage structural
reforms, which is to lay a sound basis for Pakistan to qualify for
the Extended Structural Adjustment Facility (ESAF) of the
International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif has already launched the National
Debt Retirement Program which has so far attracted 450 million
dollars including commitments made by overseas Pakistanis.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani government has embarked upon a revolutionary
program of advancing the privatization process in a more judicious
and transparent manner.
</P>
<P>
Overseas Pakistanis have so far remitted over 37 billion
dollars since 1972 through banking system, excluding the foreign
exchange remitted through other unofficial channels.
</P>
<P>
Of the total remittances, only 18 percent was utilized for
commercial and development purposes, while the rest of the major
chunk was channeled towards the consumption sector.
</P>
<P>
Sensing the huge potential of overseas capital, the present
government is determined to tap this avenue of enormous capital
and investment for revival and development of the country's
economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
