<DOCNO> XIE19970328.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy's PM Announces Mini-Budget to Prepare for EMU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi
today unveiled a widely-expected mini-budget of 15.5 trillion lira
(about 9.12 billion U.S. dollars) to prepare for the country's
entry into the single European currency.
</P>
<P>
The supplementary budget, the second this year, will help keep
the country's current budget deficit within the limits set out in
the Maastricht Treaty, he said.
</P>
<P>
The major component of the mini-budget was a levy on company
severance pay funds this year and next year, which will raise a
total of 12 trillion lira (7.06 billion dollars), Treasury and
Budget Minister Carlo Azeglio Ciampi told a news conference.
</P>
<P>
However, companies with fewer than 15 employees will be exempt
from the levy, Ciampi added.
</P>
<P>
In February, Prodi said his government was likely to announce a
spring mini-budget to ensure the country qualifies as a founder
member of the single currency.
</P>
<P>
Italy is fighting hard to convince sceptical partners in the
European Union, notably Germany, that it can put its finances
in order on a lasting basis to qualify as a founder of the
single currency which is due to be launched on January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The EU's Maastricht Treaty has set five criteria for membership
of European Monetary Union, one of which is that the budget
deficit and national debt of a member country must not exceed 3
and 60 percent respectively of its gross domestic product. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
