<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat, US Envoy Hold Talks in Rabat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RABAT, March 27 (Xinhua) -- President of the Palestinian
autonomous authority Yasser Arafat today had a two-hour meeting
with the U.S. Middle East Coordinator Dennis Ross, but no details
of their talks were given by either Palestinian or U.S. officials.
</P>
<P>
Arafat arrived here this morning to attend the 16th session of
the Al-Qods (Jerusalem) Committee of the Organization of Islamic
Conference, which opened today under the presidence of King Hassan
II of Morocco.
</P>
<P>
The Al-Qods Committee will examine the latest situation in
Jerusalem and the dangers posed against the Arab part of the city,
after Israeli Prime Minister Benyamin Netanyahu decided to build a
new settlement in the Arab part of the holy city.
</P>
<P>
The members of the committee accused Israel of trying to
"Judaize" Jerusalem by continuously carrying out plans to expand
the Jewish settlements.
</P>
<P>
King Hassan today also had a meeting with Ross, who is also the
personal envoy of U.S. President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Ross was sent by President Clinton to tap the possibility of
relaunching the Middle East peace process, which is now marked by
an overall freeze of all dialogue between Israel and the
Palestinians following the Israeli decision to build a new housing
in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Ross will return to Washington this weekend to make a report on
his talks with Arafat to President Clinton and Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
In a statement published earlier today, King Hassan urged
Israel to implement all the agreements it has signed with the
Palestinians and all the commitments made since the Madrid
International Peace Conference on the Middle East in 1992.
</P>
<P>
"The act taken recently by the Israeli administration.... made
us think that it was not serious when pretending that it wanted to
pursue the peace process on the basis agreed upon by the Madrid
conference, and that it was not aware of the grave consequences
which would result from the implementation of its decision to
build a new settlement," said the king.
</P>
<P>
He recalled that the Madrid conference decided upon the
principle of "land for peace" which should serve as the basis of
negotiating peace between Israel and Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
He also said the Palestinian people have the "imprescriptible"
rights to self-determination and the establishment of an
independent state on their fatherland with Jerusalem as its
capital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
