<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major Reforms in Economic Restructuring for 1997 Mapped out (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 27 (Xinhua) -- The State Commission for
Restructuring the Economy has listed a number of major reforms of
the country's economic structure this year, with the reform of
state-owned enterprises serving as the top priority.
</P>
<P>
In line with the strategic objectives of China's Ninth
Five-year Plan (1996-2000), the reforms also cover investment
mechanisms, social security, housing, commodity circulation,
taxation, and banking.
</P>
<P>
The government will intensify efforts to organize large-scale
state-owned corporations and enterprise groups favored with local
advantages and guided by market requirements and state policies,
and at the same time give more operating freedom to small
state-owned businesses.
</P>
<P>
Through varied forms of combination, annexation, share-holding,
purchasing, auction and bankruptcy, the restructuring of the
operation mechanisms of state companies will be strengthened so as
to make the best use of their current assets.
</P>
<P>
In the process, the commanding role of the market and the
guiding and driving forces of the government will be better
combined. With approval and coordination of relevant departments,
state assets can flow freely between different enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Those heavily-indebted and inefficient enterprises can be made
to turn out new products, have their debt burdens reshuffled by
means of coordination, merging, entrustment, and the auction of
debt ownership.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a property right transaction market, which features
annexation, purchasing and leasing, will be nurtured in order to
promote the flow of state assets. In case of annexation and
bankruptcy, the bottom-line living expenses of laid-off workers
must be guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
More efforts will be put to the establishment of a modern
enterprise system characterized by more efficient and scientific
internal management, the separation of government administration
from enterprise management, and less burdens piled up in the
enterprise's history.
</P>
<P>
Some qualified enterprises can raise money by issuing stocks
and setting up specific funds so as to improve their balance
sheet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
