<DOCNO> XIE19970328.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major Reforms in Economic Restructuring for 1997 Mapped out  (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The government will cut investment in enterprises, so that they
can become fully adapted to market economy. Enterprises should be
encouraged to invest in profitable projects, while the government
puts more money in public projects and infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
Consequently, the decisions of corporate executives will be
restricted by the risk of banking loans, and banks in turn will
have bigger decision-making power in providing loans while holding
responsibility for the risk of their loans.
</P>
<P>
To coordinate the reform of state-owned enterprises, the reform
of social security system, which mainly covers old-age pension,
medical care and unemployment, will be stepped up.
</P>
<P>
With regard to housing reform, houses will no longer be part of
welfare given to workers and government employees, who in the
future will have to pay a growing sum of rent, but with a certain
amount of subsidies at the same time.
</P>
<P>
In addition, public housing funds will be collected from all
work units.
</P>
<P>
The prices of commodity houses will be made more reasonable,
and banks will provide more housing loans to encourage more people
to buy houses.
</P>
<P>
In commodity circulation sector, concrete measures will be
explored to incorporate the grain purchasing prices of the
government and market prices. Meanwhile, the government will
be more capable of regulating and stabilizing the grain market.
</P>
<P>
As to cotton transactions, the form of cotton trade fairs will
be improved, in which cotton producers and buyers will have the
chance to hold face-to-face business talks.
</P>
<P>
And the government will boost the development of wholesale
markets, used goods markets, and store chains.
</P>
<P>
And in financial reform, the on-going revenue transfer system
and revenue-sharing system will continue to be implemented so as
to beef up the macro-control power of the central government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
