<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe to Curb Money Supply Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 27 (Xinhua) -- The Reserve Bank of Zimbabwe (RBZ)
today pledged to step up efforts to control money supply growth to
contain inflationary pressures.
</P>
<P>
The bank warned the inflation in Zimbabwe could derail one of
the most dramatic economic recoveries ever experienced since 1980.
</P>
<P>
RBZ Governor Leonard Tsumba, delievering his traditional
twice-yearly monetary statement in Harare, appealed for support from
the government to contain the runaway budget deficit, which is
expected to exceed 11 percent of GDP in the year to June 1997.
</P>
<P>
''Money supply growth will, therefore, have to be curbed. In this
regard, the out-turn for January 1997, which saw broad money grow at
a reduced rate of 23.9 percent, is a welcome development and a
movement in the right direction,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
He added Zimbabwe's foreign reserves have plummeted from a high of
five months import cover last September to just three months cover
due to speculation and increased import demand.
</P>
<P>
He said the country's inflation would be around 19-21 percent by
June and below 20 percent for the rest of the year.
</P>
<P>
On economic performance, he said in 1997, the bank was forecasting
that real growth would be about five percent due to the generally
favourable 1996/97 agricultural season. enditem

