<HEADLINE> Chinese Official on Economic Returns, Social Effects from Films </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 27 (Xinhua) -- A senior Chinese official said
here today at a film forum that film-makers should produce more
and better films that depict socialist cultural and ethical
progress, and gain more economic returns while attaching
importance to the social effect.
</P>
<P>
Ding Guangen, member of the Political Bureau of the Communist
Party of China (CPC) Central Committee and also member of the
Central Committee's Secretariat, said at the three-day forum which
ended today that film-producers and government departments at all
levels produced more films that carry forward socialist cultural
and ethical progress, and quite a number of them gained popularity
over the past year.
</P>
<P>
Government departments have enhanced their leadership in the
field, conduct in-depth reform, and increased investment, Ding
noted, adding that "the general situation is good".
</P>
<P>
Ding said the Party pays great attention to the development of
films, and Communist Party General Secretary Jiang Zemin has made
many remarks on it, saying that China should produce more fine
works and pursue film prosperity.
</P>
<P>
China is still short of excellent films, Ding noted, and the
film-making industry is still faced with difficulties and problems
that cannot be underestimated. Film-makers and officials should
redouble efforts to vitalize Chinese films, he added.
</P>
<P>
Ding underlined that films should have ideological contents,
artistry and should be appreciable and enjoyable. He pointed out
that film-makers should consider the market, gaining social
effects and economic returns at the same time.
</P>
<P>
And the film circle should continue to deepen the reform and
have a healthy development, Ding said.
</P>
<P>
The forum was held one year after the National Film
Conference. Participants studied the remarks of President Jiang
Zemin and the late leader Deng Xiaoping on films, exchanged their
experience and offered a lot of suggestions at the forum.  
</P>
