<HEADLINE> Russians Hold Nationwide Protest for Social Guarantees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 27 (Xinhua) -- About 20 million Russians turned
out today to take part in a well-organized protest action under
the slogan "For work, justice and social guarantees."
</P>
<P>
The nationwide protest, initiated and organized by the
Federation of Independent Trade Union of Russia (FITUR) almost a
month ago, is held mainly to demand repayment of wage and pension
arrears, which are running at about 9 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
"The main thing is ensure that the protest action result in the
breaking off the mechanism which is conducive to the emergence of
wage arrears," said FITUR leader Mikhail Shmakov.
</P>
<P>
During the nationwide protest, 7 million protesters are expected
to go on strike while the rest will march in demonstration or
participate in pickets and rallies.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin said today at a regular
meeting of the government that strikes and protest action of the
trade unions cannot solve problems.
</P>
<P>
The premier meanwhile pointed out that during the first three
months of the year real incomes of the population had increased by
4 percent from the same period of 1996 and the size of the
population whose incomes are below the subsistence level was
reduced by 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
But Chernomyrdin stressed that "trade union strikes are a vivid
and objective indication of the acuteness of accumulated
problems." 
</P>
