<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe to Get Bumper Harvest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean commercial farmers today
said they are predicting another bumper agricultural harvest this
season despite earlier concern about reduced output due to heavy
rains early this year.
</P>
<P>
In a report released in Harare, the Commercial Farmers Union (CFU)
Vice-President for Commodities Bob Swift said for example, total
output of the staple maize crop from all farming sectors was
estimated at two million tonnes, while 258,000 tonnes of seed cotton
were expected from both large and small scale farmers.
</P>
<P>
He said soyabean production was estimated at 95,000 tonnes in the
current season, which market experts said was slightly below forecast
by about 10-15 percent due to waterlogging caused by heavy rains.
</P>
<P>
Coffee production is forecast at 12,000 tonnes and at least 30 to
40 percent of the crop has been forward sold to take advantage of the
buoyant prices, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said winter wheat production was this year estimated to reach
300,000 tonnes, while a total of 15,000 tonnes of flowers and 13,000
tonnes of fresh produce was expected this year. enditem

