<HEADLINE> Hun Sen: U.S. Senators Can Not Annul Cambodian Court Verdict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Cambodian Second Prime
Minister Hun Sen said here today that U.S. senators have no right
to annul Cambodian court verdict.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks while talking to reporters about the case
of Prince Norodom Sirivudh at an alliance forming ceremony between
his Cambodian People's Party (CPP) and the Khmer Citizen Party
this evening.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen said "the whole U.S. senators cannot annul the verdict
handed down by a Cambodian court," referring to the fact that
three U.S. senators wrote to and pleaded him to allow exiled
Sirivudh return to Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
Sirivudh, former Cambodian Foreign Minister, was sentenced in
absent to 10 years jail on charges of plotting to kill Hun Sen and
illegal weapons possession last February. But he went into exile
in France before the trial.
</P>
<P>
"Even the King cannot pardon Sirivudh if the culprit has not
served in jail for seven years, two thirds of his prison term,"
Hun Sen said, adding that "Sirivudh must be jailed first."
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen reaffirmed his insistence that royal family members
forgo their royal status if they seek office, suggesting the royal
family itself initiate a constitutional amendment to remove royal
family out of politics. 
</P>
