<HEADLINE> Nigerian to Represent ECOWAS in Liberia Electoral </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Retired Nigerian diplomat Issac
Sagay has been appointed as the representative of the Economic
Community of West African States (ECOWAS) to the Liberia
Electoral Commission.
</P>
<P>
The official News Agency of Nigeria quoted a Foreign Ministry
source as saying in the Nigerian capital of Abuja today that
Sagay has left for Liberia last week to assume duties.
</P>
<P>
Sagay last served in Spain as a diplomat, the report said.
</P>
<P>
According to a decision of the ECOWAS ministerial meeting in
Monrovia last month, the Liberian legislative and presidential
elections set for May 30 will be organized by an independent
commission of 10 members.
</P>
<P>
Liberia's three major factions, namely, the National Patriotic
Front of Liberia, the United Liberation Movement and the Liberia
Peace Council, will produce one member each.
</P>
<P>
Another four members will be produced by the alliance of seven
political parties, women's organizations, youth organizations and
labor and trade unions, respectively.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations, the Organization of African Unity and the
ECOWAS will each produce a member without voting power.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations, the United States and the Netherlands have
agreed to help fund the elections that will lead to the final end
of Liberia's seven-year civil war that has claimed 150,000 lives.
