<DOCNO> XIE19970328.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lome Summit Urges UN to Set Up Peace Mechanism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOME, March 27 (Xinhua) -- The extraordinary summit of the
Organization of African Unity ended here today, recommending to the UN
Security Council the setting up of a mechanism for the implementation
of the UN/OAU peace plan on Zaire.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement issued here today at the end of the
meeting, the Central Organ of the OAU Mechanism for Conflict
Prevention, Management and Resolution requested that the secretaries
general of the OAU and the UN to make nececcasry consultations to this
end.
</P>
<P>
The five-point peace plan on the Zaire crisis, adopted by the UN
Security Council, provides for an immediate ceasefire, the withdrawal
of foreign forces, negotiations and elections and the protection of
refugees.
</P>
<P>
The two-day summit, attended by 30 African countries, reiterated
its grave concern over the deteriorating situation in the
Great Lakes region, especially the current armed conflict in eastern
Zaire.
</P>
<P>
It called for immediate negotiations between the government of
Zaire and the Alliance of Democratic Forces for the Liberation of
Zaire-Congo so as to lead to a ceasefire and complete cessation of
hostilities to pave the way for the UN peace plan.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that the OAU central organ authorized OAU
Secretary General Salim Ahmed Salim to "establish contacts with
the leadership" of the Zairean rebels led by Laurent Kabila,
whose fighters are fighting against the government army in
eastern Zaire.
</P>
<P>
All types of foreign military intervention and the use of
mercenaries in Zaire were condemned by the central organ, according
to the statement.
</P>
<P>
The central organ also requested Salim to take appropriate
practical measures to assess the situation of refugees and displaced
persons in eastern Zaire and all other countries of the region.
</P>
<P>
All the parties to the conflict were urged to create safe and
secure conditions to faciliate the delivery of humanitarian and relief
assistance to refugees and internally displaced persons.
</P>
<P>
It underscored the importance of convening an international
conference on peace, security, stability and development in the Great
Lakes region under the auspices of the OAU and the UN, said the
statement.
</P>
<P>
All the peace initiatives for resolving the Zaire conflict were
welcomed, but the central organ stressed the need to ensure proper and
adequate coordination of all these initiatives.
</P>
<P>
However, the delegation of the Zairean government for the summit
had reservations about a few points of the statement, including the
condemnation of the use of mercenaries in Zaire, the call for
immediate negotiations before a ceasefire, and the establishing of
OAU contacts with the rebel leadership.
</P>
<P>
The summit, which centered on finding ways to resolve the conflict
in Zaire, was attended by 30 African countries with the two warring
sides of Zaire represented.
</P>
<P>
OAU chief Salim, UN Secretary General Koffi Annan and
representatives of the United States, Britain, France, Germany and the
European Union were also present at the summit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970328.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. First Lady Begins Visit to Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 27 (Xinhua) -- United States First Lady Hillary
Clinton arrived in Uganda from Tanzania this evening on a
three-day official visit.
</P>
<P>
She was welcomed by the Ugandan first Lady Janet Museveni at
Entebbe International Airport, 40 km south of Kampala.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued on arrival, Hillary said she was happy
to be in Uganda and looked forward to seeing the progress taking
place in the country after it emerged from a decade of crisis.
She said that Uganda is known to have one of the most vibrant
economies in Africa with a rapid growth, increasing investments
and expanding exports. She commended the establishment of a new
constitution and democratically elected leaders and was
especially happy to note that women are adding to and benefiting
from these gains.
</P>
<P>
Hillary commended the strong ties existing between the U.S.A.
and Uganda and said her country is proud of its partnership with
Uganda on the important development issues which are bearing
fruit. She said the successes in development efforts reflect the
courage and dynamism of the people of Uganda as well as the
committed leadership of President Y. Museveni.
</P>
<P>
Uganda is her fifth stop before Eritrea on a six-nation tour
of Africa which has so far taken her through Senegal, South
Africa, Zimbabwe and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, she will deliver an open speech on issues related
to environment, women, AIDS and democracy.
</P>
<P>
She is also expected to visit USAID-funded projects in Uganda
and meet President Museveni and other officials on bilateral
relations and U.S.-African relations in general. 
</P>
