<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Extends Military Observer Mission in Liberia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 27 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Security Council today decided to extend the mandate of the United
Nations Military Observer Million in Liberia until June 30, 1997.
</P>
<P>
In a resolution adopted unanimously today, the Security Council
emphasized that the holding of free and fair elections scheduled
for May 30 was an essential phase of the peace process in Liberia.
</P>
<P>
While stressing the ultimate responsibility of Liberian people
for achieving peace and national reconciliation, the council urged
the international community to provide financial, logistical and
other assistance to the electoral process in Liberia, and to
provide additional support for the Economic Community of West
African States Monitoring Group (ECOMOG).
</P>
<P>
The Security Council also urged all Liberian parties to
cooperate with the peace process, including by respecting human
rights and facilitating humanitarian activities and disarmament.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Ambassador Wang Xuexian said at the council today that
the final settlement of the Liberia issue depends on the Liberian
people only. Starting from the interests of the state and the
people, leaders of all Liberian parties should show their sense of
political duty, he said.
</P>
<P>
Wang said that China has always firmly supported the Economic
Community of West African States to solve the problems in the
region according to the United Nations Charter. Together with the
international community, China will make its own contribution to
earlier realization of peace and stability and ushering in a new
era of reconstruction and development in Liberia, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
