<HEADLINE> Ethiopian Former Deputy PM on Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian former Deputy
Prime Minister Tamirat Layne today appeared in the federal
supreme court along with eight others alleged accomplices on
charges of embezzlement.
</P>
<P>
Tamirat, who was relieved of his post for disciplinary reasons
in October 1996, has been charged with three counts of abuse of
power and holdering 11 million U.S. Dollars in foreign banks.
</P>
<P>
The first law suit filed against the former deputy prime
minister indicated that he intervened in negotiations between the
government and a private trading company that faced business
hurdles and demanded for payment.
</P>
<P>
Tamirat was accused of receiving 16 million U.S. Dollars from
Sheik Mohammed Al Amoudi and shared the money with his alleged
accomplices. Tamirat himself took 9 million of the 16 million
U.S. Dollars, according to the charge.
</P>
<P>
The prosecution said Tamirat, as part of his bid to compensate
the company, ordered the sale of 1,000 tons of state coffee that
was sold for 3.6 million U.S. Dollars of which the former deputy
prime minister took 1.8 million U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The second charge leveled against Tamirat alleged he laid the
favorable condition for Ramis International Private Limited
Company to be the sole supplier of construction materials to four
regions. Tamirat was the head of the company and ordered the four
regions to buy construction materials from the company.
</P>
<P>
The third law suit filed against Tamirat said he unlawfully
helped Soja Contractor win a tender put in for the Mile-Assab
road project for which he was paid one million U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Tamirat has voiced objections against the first and third
charges, saying he would present to the court his objections.
</P>
<P>
The trail was adjourned until April 15.
</P>
<P>
Tamirat was prime minister of the transitional government from
1991 to 1995. He became deputy prime minister and minister of
defense in August 1995. He was also president of the Amhara
National Democratic Movement and deputy chairman of the ruling
Ethiopian People's Revolutionary Democratic Front. 
</P>
</TEXT>
