<HEADLINE> U.S. to Cut Air Force at Base in Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 27 (Xinhua) -- The United States will cut the
number of U.S. Air Force personnel assigned to a base in turkey by
up to 50 percent in the next 18 months, the Defense Department
announced in a statement on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The statement said reduction of the 24,000 U.S. Air Force staff
permanently assigned to Incirlik would begin immediately, and is
expected to continue through September 1998.
</P>
<P>
The move "is part of the general realignment of U.S. bases in
Europe, in which more than 800 U.S. military installations have
been returned to European countries, reduced or place on standby
status, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. government is not reducing its commitment to Europe
or Turkey," which "remains a vital U.S. ally and key regional
partner," the statement added.
</P>
<P>
Defense officials said the whittling down of U.S. troops
strength would not affect a separate operation at Incirlik for
U.S. flights to enforce a no-fly zone over northern Iraq.
</P>
</TEXT>
