<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Existing Home Sales Rise to Near-Record Level </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Sales of previously owned
homes in the U.S. increased by 9 percent in February to the second
highest level on record, the U.S. National Association of Realtors
said today.
</P>
<P>
The association said in a report that existing single-family
homes sold at a 4.26 million annual rate in the month, up from
3.91 million in January,
</P>
<P>
The level of sales in February was the strongest since last May
when existing homes sold at a record 4.28 million annual rate.
</P>
<P>
For all of 1996, the sale of previously owned home totaled 4.09
million, the best in 18 years.
</P>
<P>
By region in February, sales soared by 13.6 percent in the
West, 10 percent in the Midwest, 8.6 percent in the Northeast and
5.5 percent in the South.
</P>
<P>
The median price of an existing home was 117,500 dollars last
month, up by 3.1 percent from a year earlier. The median is the
midpoint, meaning half of the homes sold for more and half for
less.
</P>
<P>
U.S. analysts said that the strong sale resulted from mild
temperatures, lower interest rates and health U.S. economy.
</P>
<P>
However, with the U.S. Federal Reserve starting to increase
interest rates, many analysts are expecting a more moderate --
though still good -- rate of sales this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
