<HEADLINE> France Calls for Exceptional EU Meeting on Middle East </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 28 (Xinhua) -- France today called for an
exceptional meeting of the European Union (EU) countries to help
relaunch the Middle East peace process, which is now experiencing
another crisis.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Ministry spokesman Jacques Rummelhardt said that
such a meeting should be held at the level of political directors
of the foreign ministries of EU countries.
</P>
<P>
The date for holding such a meeting has not been decided yet,
said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
France has also expressed its deep concern over the
comprehensive blockade of the Palestinian territories by Israeli
security forces, who have blocked all accesses into Israel and
Jerusalem from the West Bank and the Gaza Strip, after a suicide
attack by a Palestinian militant on Thursday last week killed four
in Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have intensified their protests after Israel
decided to build a new Jewish settlement in an Arab district of
East Jerusalem Israel has occupied since 1967.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Middle East Coordinator Dennis Ross is on a mission in the
Middle East and has held talks with Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister Benyamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Ross has asked Arafat to help defuse the tension between
Palestinians and Israelis, and stop Palestinian militants from
staging more attacks on Israeli targets.
</P>
<P>
France said the Israeli blockade of Palestinian territories is
unfairly punishing the whole Palestinian people, has gravely
endangered Palestinian economy and has prevented Palestinians from
going to their places of worship in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
"This is why France hopes that the Palestinians, whatever
their beliefs are, could have free access to all the holy sites of
Jerusalem," said the foreign ministry spokesman.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Minister Herve de Charette had a telephone
conversation with his Egyptian counterpart, Amr Moussa, this
morning, and both of them expressed deep concern over "the
degradation of the situation in the Middle East," said the
spokesman. 
</P>
