<HEADLINE> Leading US Network Supplier Expands Investment in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 28 (Xinhua) -- Bay Networks, one of the major US
suppliers of computer networks, has made an cumulative investment
of two million US dollars in China since it inaugurated business
here in 1994, said a senior representative of the company.
</P>
<P>
David Shrigley, vice-president of Bey Networks, told a press
conference today that the investment will further increase in the
coming years, for "the appealing market potential that no company
can reject."
</P>
<P>
During the past three years, Bay Networks registered a
consecutive increase of 100 percent-plus annually in its business
income. Through the cooperation with China Construction Bank, one
of the country's largest commercial banks, Bay helped launch the
country's first frame relay network, which largely quickened the
data transmission in the computer system of the bank.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the company provided model networks for two
national-level information network projects of the country, the
Golden Card, and Golden Customs Programs.
</P>
<P>
Shrigley said that the company is now seeking more extensive
involvement in China's information modernization drive, and will
expand the cooperation and exchanges with the domestic network
companies over the coming years.
</P>
<P>
So far, Bay has opened two representative offices in Beijing
and Shanghai, providing the country with the sophisticated network
products ranging from high-speed routers, ATM (asynchronous
transport mode) switching gear, to network management systems.
</P>
<P>
Established in 1994 through a merger between two US network
firms, Bay Networks now has more than 120 branchs and 1,000 sales
agents throughout the world. Its business revenues stood at two
billion dollars in 1996.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970328.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Government Okeys Deregulation Package </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, March 28 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese government today
approved a revised package of deregulation measures to invigorate
the economy, create jobs, cut red tape and provide foreign
companies with greater access to the Japanese market.
</P>
<P>
The package is designed to reduce or revise a vast range of
regulations that foreign critics say impinge on fair
competition and serve as a barrier to trade with Japan.
</P>
<P>
It is the final part of a three-year program containing 2,823
measures to deregulate areas such as financial services,
communications, housing, distribution, transport, energy, labor
and education.
</P>
<P>
The government says it aims to set out clear-cut rules,
inspect whether they are observed and punish violations. It will
check progress in the autumn on the implementation of the
measures.
</P>
<P>
The package contains 890 new deregulatory steps,
including allowing brokerage houses to offer comprehensive
accounts from which public utility charges are automatically
debited, permitting construction of higher buildings in city areas
to create more living space, and lifting a ban on sales of vitamin
compounds at convenience stores.
</P>
<P>
Also among the items aimed at moving Japanese standards toward
international levels is a revision in industrial standards and
allowing more foreign lawyers to work in Japan.
</P>
<P>
A number of items are designed to reduce government
intervention in determining new entrants into certain industries,
such as taxis, domestic airlines and foreign currency
transactions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970328.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
