<HEADLINE> India, South Africa Establish Strategic Partnership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 28 (Xinhua) -- India and South Africa today
entered a strategic partnership for mutual consultations on
regional and global security issues.
</P>
<P>
The two countries outlined their future cooperation course in a
</P>
<P>
"Red Fort Declaration" on strategic partnership between India
and South Africa signed by Indian Prime Minister Deve Gowda and
visiting South African President Nelson Mandela after the latter
was accorded a civic reception at Red Fort here this evening.
Mandela came here last night on a three-day official visit to
India.
</P>
<P>
The 11-point declaration spells out the South African position
welcoming India's recent initiatives to promote friendship and
good-neighborliness in the South Asian region.
</P>
<P>
The declaration stresses the need for an equitable balance in
the composition of an expanded
Security Council of the United Nations to provide a constructive
voice to the aspirations of the developing countries.
</P>
<P>
In the declaration, India and South Africa have expressed their
resolve to work for non-aligned movement's (NAM) increasing
effectiveness in the promotion of political, socio-economic
justice and disarmament.
</P>
<P>
Mandela declined to comment on the nature of security
cooperation envisaged between India and South Africa, saying that
there has to be great degree of confidentiality in this kind of
relationship.
</P>
<P>
During summit talks between Gowda and Mandela here today, the
two sides agreed to intensify bilateral cooperation in various
areas including trade and industry as well as science and
technology, official sources said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
