-- The 39 men and women who committed suicide were members of a
cult known as Heaven's Gate, the authorities said. They left
behind detailed videotapes describing their intention and appeared
to believe that the Hale-Bopp Comet now streaking across the sky
was their ticket to heaven.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- The National Cancer Institute yesterday recommended that
women in their forties get screening mammograms for breast cancer
every year or two, reversing an earlier position that had prompted
harsh criticism and an emotional debate.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- Martin Luther King's son met James Earl Ray at a Tennessee
prison. Dexter King asked,"Did you kill my father?" Ray
emphatically denied shooting the civil-rights leader in 1968. "I
believe you," King said. The King family backs a trial for Ray,
believed close to death.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Times:
</P>
<P>
-- The stock and bond markets nose-dived yesterday as investors
became convinced that the Federal Reserve will have to raise
interest rates substantially more in coming months to slow the
speeding economy.
</P>
<P>
USA Today:
</P>
<P>
-- President Clinton and House Speaker Newt Gingrich may want
to postpone tax cuts as they try to hammer out a balanced budget.
but most Americans say don't.  
