<DOCNO> XIE19970328.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interviewees Refute Involvement in US Political Donations (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Before I visited the US this time, I had no plan to meet with
President Clinton. After my arrival in Washington, I was told at
the last moment that there would be the possibility for me to meet
with Clinton. Because my agenda was so tight at that time, and I
did not have anything to say to him, so I politely declined (the
invitation)," Wang said.
</P>
<P>
Afterwards, on an occasion when a lot of people were present,
Wang met with President Clinton informally. "Both sides referred
to no other topics except expressing greetings to each other," he
said.
</P>
<P>
It is sheer nonsense that some US reports described this
meeting as something to do with the political donations case, Wang
said seriously. "I always talk about business affairs as a
businessman should do, and never take part and meddle in other
country's internal affairs," he said.
</P>
<P>
Wang also mentioned a case concerning the smuggling of 2,000
AK-47 automatic rifles which occurred in the US last year. Some
people in the US purposedly imposed the charge upon the Poly
company whose president is Wang.
</P>
<P>
And now, after one year has passed, they again connected the
case with his meeting with Clinton as well as with the alleged
political donations. This action was intended to make a false
charge against and frame him, and was done with ulterior
motives.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970328.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interviewees Refute Involvement in US Political Donations (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Poly began to export guns for civilian use to the U.S. from the
end of 1984 while strictly abiding by the relevant Chinese laws
and regulations on management of gun export and the
U.S. regulations on gun import, Wang Jun said.
</P>
<P>
All goods exported to the U.S. had import certificates issued
by the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms, under the U.S.
Department of the Treasury. Poly never undertook business which
might violate both Chinese and U.S. laws, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. President issued a decree to ban importing guns for
civilian use from China in 1994. Poly immediately stopped the
business, withdrew the company's office in the U.S., and has since
never exported a single rife or a single bullet to the U.S., he
added.
</P>
<P>
Wang held that China's related authorities have made a serious
and overall investigation into the so-called gun-smuggling case
since it was disclosed last year.
</P>
<P>
"I can say responsibly that the case has nothing with Poly
Technologies Inc. and its staffers," he said. "Actually, it was
some Americans who registered a company with a name similar
to 'Poly' after Poly withdrew its office in 1994, and got a person
who was fired by Poly many years ago involved in."
</P>
<P>
"Such deeds are illegal not only in the U.S., but also in
China. I do believe there will be a fair judgment of this case,
and truth will finally prove that the case has nothing to do with
Poly," Wang told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
"I would solemnly declare that I have never visited the U.S. or
met with U.S. President Clinton for the purpose of Poly's
business. CITIC, Poly and I myself have never got involved in the
so-called political donations," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I am strongly indignant at some reports appeared in the
U.S. news media, which have severely damaged the reputations of
CITIC, Poly and mine," he said. "If necessary, we will resort to
laws for resolution."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
