<HEADLINE> Interviewees Refute Involvement in US Political Donations (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
During his interview with Xinhua, Zheng Hongye, former chairman
of the China Council for the Promotion of International Trade
(CCPIT), expressed great indignation at some US news media's
groundless fabrications and vilification that the council was
involved in the case of "political donations".
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that those people harbored ulterior motives and
resorted to mean tricks, and their acts could only be regarded as
attempts to undermine Sino-US relations and the growth of Sino-US
economic and trade ties.
</P>
<P>
He recalled that he headed a delegation of Chinese enterprises
to the United States in March 1995 at the invitation of the
American Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
As usual, it was purely a business trip, he said. Johnny Chung,
president of the Automated Intelligent System Inc. of the United
States, hinted to Zheng that he could arrange a meeting between
the delegation and the US president.
</P>
<P>
"Being the CCPIT chairman," Zheng said, "It is beneficial and
in line with the international practice to take the opportunity to
express Chinese entrepreneurs' views and wishes of cooperation to
the US government leaders when the Sino-US trade relations were at
a low ebb."
</P>
<P>
The delegation met with President Clinton on March 11 after
Clinton's weekly national broadcast speech. Zheng conveyed to
Clinton the hope of Chinese economic and trade circles that there
could be a good trading and investment environment for the growth
of Sino-US economic and trade relations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970328.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interviewees Refute Involvement on US Political Donations (5) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
That was all about the matter, Zheng said.
</P>
<P>
"We never paid Mr. Chung any fees," Zheng said sternly and with
the force of justice. "There is no such thing as providing
political donations through Mr Chung or someone else. We hope that
those who have ulterior motives stop such mean tricks to distract
attention and put the blame on others, and give up attempts to
make trouble for and undermine the steady improvement of Sino-US
relations."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, some US news media dragged the renting of a wharf in
Long Beach by the China Ocean Shipping Company (COSCO) into the
issue when fabricating the news of "political donations".
</P>
<P>
Since the news media have made distorted reports on the legal
operations of the COSCO, Cosco America Inc. President Ma Zehua noted,
it is necessary to clarify the real situation.
</P>
<P>
Ma said that COSCO started to rent the Long Beach Port back in
1981. With the growth of the Sino-US trade, the turnover of the
COSCO's containers increased and its liners stopped at western
American ports three times a week.
</P>
<P>
To develop the business better still, according to Ma, COSCO
planned to rent a container wharf in the regions of Long Beach or
Los Angeles. Having made surveys for a long period of time and
conducted feasibility surveys of some ports in southern
California, Cosco America Inc. signed an agreement to rent a
closed former navy wharf in Long Beach with the port
administration on April 14, 1994. The agreement officially took
effect on November 15. The negotiations were conducted through
lawyers and agreed to the laws and legal procedures of the United
States.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the agreement, the Long Beach Port had already started
planned development of the wharf facilities.
</P>
</TEXT>
