<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Life Expectancy Edges Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, March 28 (Xinhua) -- The average life expectancy of men
and women in Japan edged up marginally between 1990 and 1995, the
Japanese Ministry of Health and Welfare said today.
</P>
<P>
The 1995 statistics show that the average life expectancy for
Japanese men rose from 76.37 to 76.38 years and for women from
82.83 to 82.85 years.
</P>
<P>
Officials at the ministry said that without the 1995 Kobe
earthquake, in which more than 5,000 Japanese died, the figure
would have been higher.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry conducts census and research on average life
expectancy in Japan every five years.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese are well-known for their longevity, which is
attributed in large part to their healthy diet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
