<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Upper House Passes Fiscal '97 Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, March 28 (Xinhua) -- Japan's House of Councillors, the
upper house of parliament, today passed the fiscal 1997 budget
with backing of the ruling Liberal Democratic Party and its two
allies, the Social Democratic Party and New Party Sakigake.
</P>
<P>
The 77.39 trillion yen (645 billion U.S. dollars) budget, which
cleared the House of Representatives, the lower house, on
March 5, was passed by 141 votes to 104.
</P>
<P>
The 1997 budget, which goes from April this year to March 1998,
is three percent bigger than the initial budget for fiscal 1996.
</P>
<P>
The planned rise in consumption tax from 3 to 5 percent in
fiscal 1997 and the abolition of special tax breaks will generate
an additional 5 trillion yen (42 billion dollars) in revenue.
</P>
<P>
General expenditure, excluding obligatory costs such as
national debt servicing and tax grants to local governments, are
set to increase 1.5 percent from a year earlier to 43.81 trillion
yen (365 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Of that, 4.95 trillion yen (41 billion dollars) will go on
defense, 1.17 trillion yen (10 billion dollars) on official
development assistance, 9.74 trillion yen (81 billion dollars) on
public works projects and 14.55 trillion yen (121 billion dollars)
on social security costs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
