<DOCNO> XIE19970328.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-28 13:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OIC Expresses Support for Mideast Peace, PNA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 28 (Xinhua) -- The Jerusalem Committee of the
Organization of Islamic Conference (OIC) affirmed its support
to the Middle East peace process and the Palestinian National
Authority, according to reports reaching here from Rabat, the
capital of Morocco.
</P>
<P>
In a final communique released at the end of the 16th session
of the committee in Rabat Thursday evening, the Jerusalem
Committee headed by Morocco's King Hassan condemned the Israeli
measures obstructing the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The committee urged Islamic countries to reconsider their
relations with Israel, including the closing down of offices and
the suspension of missions, until Israel abided by
U.N. resolutions and implemented agreements signed between the
PNA and Israel in accordance with the Madrid peace conference and
the Oslo accord.
</P>
<P>
The communique called upon the international community to
oblige Israel to adhere to peace accords with the Palestinians
and to resume negotiations with Syria from the point reached
before suspension.
</P>
<P>
It also condemned Israel's persistence in its settlement
policies in Jerusalem and other occupied Palestinian and Arab
territories.
</P>
<P>
It called for an immediate cessation of construction works in
Jebel Abu Ghneim, or Har Homa in East Jerusalem and all other
measures aiming to change the political, geographic, legal
and historic status of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
It called upon OIC Secretary General Izzidine Iraki to
undertake necessary contacts with international and regional
organizations and specialized agencies to study ways and means to
preserve the historic, cultural and religious heritage of
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The committee reaffirmed in the communique that the city of
Jerusalem constituted an inseparable part of the occupied
Palestinian territories in 1967, adding that Israel has to pull
out from these territories in accordance with international
legitimate resolutions and the land-for-peace principle which
demand Israel withdraw from all Palestinian and Arab
territories occupied during 1967 Mideast War.
</P>
<P>
The committee called once again for the restoration by the
Palestinian people of their firm and irrevocable national rights,
including their right to return home, self-determination, and the
establishment of their independent state on their national soil
with Jerusalem as its capital.
</P>
<P>
It also called on Israel to release Palestinian prisoners and
to lift the economic siege imposed against Palestinian territories.
</P>
<P>
The 16th session of the OIC Jerusalem Committee began in Rabat
Thursday evening at foreign ministerial level. PNA President
Yasser Arafat attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Committee is an offshoot of the OIC, which
includes the PNA, Jordan, Syria, Lebanon, Egypt, Iraq, Morocco,
Saudi Arabia, Bangladesh, Senegal, Pakistan, Niger, Mauritania,
Guinea, Iran and Indonesia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970328.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, Hong Kong Combine to Have Crack at World Titles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Chinese players will pair up with
their Hong Kong counterparts at the World Table Tennis
Championships, the Chinese Table Tennis Association (CTTA)
announced here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
China's world No. 5 Wang Tao will combine with Hong Kong top
women player Chai Po Wa at the world championships to be held in
Manchester, England, from April 24 to May 5.
</P>
<P>
Liu Wei, who along with Wang won the mixed doubles title for
second straight time in last championships in Tianjin, has retired
from national service to play for a Japanese club.
</P>
<P>
"This combination is a celebration of Hong Kong's return to the
motherland," said Xu Yinsheng, chief of the Chinese Table Tennis
Association.
</P>
<P>
China will resume the exercise of sovereignty of Hong Kong on
July 1.
</P>
<P>
Chai Po Wa, ranked 10th in the world, will also pair up with
Qiao Yunping in the women's doubles event. The 29-year-old Qiao
has been called back from Germany for her last national cap.
</P>
<P>
Chai, who plays a wicked game in penhold grip, has been
training in Beijing for 20 days.  
</P>
</TEXT>
