<HEADLINE> Olympic Champs Lead Chinese Team in Table Tennis Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 28 (Xinhua) -- Olympic double medalists Liu
Guoliang and Deng Yaping are going to lead a 25-member Chinese
team in the World Table Tennis Championships starting on April 24
in Manchester, England.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese team comprises 12 men and 13 women players. The
backbone of the Chinese men's squad is formed by Liu Guoliang,
who last September added World Cup title to his two Olympic
titles, world No. 1 and defending world singles champion Kong
Linghui, defensive player Ding Song and veterans Wang Tao and Ma
Wenge, said team chief Li Furong.
</P>
<P>
Ma, Wang and Ding combined to lift the men's team trophy after
edging defending champions Sweden 3-2, kicking off a Chinese
clean sweep of seven titles in the 1995 championships in northern
Chinese city Tianjin.
</P>
<P>
Deng Yaping, who has bagged 15 world titles and four Olympic
gold medals in her 10-year-long career, tops the Chinese women
team.
</P>
<P>
The 24-year-old Deng, along with four youngsters -- Yang Ying
(world No. 4), Li Ju (No.6), Wang Chen (No.7) and Wang Nan
(No.9), will have a shot at the women's team top honor, said
coach Lu Yuansheng.
</P>
<P>
The oldest of the men's players is 30-year-old Wang Tao, who
has competed in four world championships and swept the doubles
and mixed titles in last two worlds.
</P>
<P>
The youngest are Ma Lin and Liu Guozheng, both 17. Liu caught
attention as he took the singles title in the Globe Youth
Championships in February. He has no connection with Liu
Guoliang.
</P>
<P>
Former world doubles champion Qiao Yunping, 29, is the oldest
player on the women's team. She has been called back from
Germany for her last national cap.
</P>
<P>
Xu Yinsheng, chief of the Chinese Table Tennis Association,
said it was impossible for the Chinese team to repeat a clean
sweep of the titles in Manchester.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese men's players have no advantage over their
European and South Korean rivals," said Xu, also president of the
International Table Tennis Federation.
</P>
<P>
"Sweden's Jan-Ove Waldner and Belarus' Vladimir Samsonov are
the top threats for the Chinese players," Xu added.
</P>
<P>
The 31-year-old Waldner, who won Sweden's only gold medal in
the Barcelona Olympics, regained form at the Qatar Open in
February, where he took the singles event after leading Sweden to
the team top podium.
</P>
<P>
Samsonov, 20, who has composure beyond his age, has beaten all
of the European top players to clinch the world No.3 ranking.
</P>
<P>
To upset the Chinese most, Samsonov has twice overcome the
Chinese "secret weapon" Ding Song, who jumped to fame after
ending the singles run of then world No. 1 Jean-Michael Saive of
Belgium and winning a crucial point in the team final at the
Tianjin Worlds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
