<HEADLINE> ESCAP Marks Its 50th Anniversary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 28 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Economic and
Social Commission for Asia and the Pacific (ESCAP) today observed
its 50th anniversary, stressing its role and achievements over the
past 50 years.
</P>
<P>
"As the main economic and social development center within the
United Nations system in the Asia and Pacific region, ESCAP plays
a multi-faced role as the only intergovernmental forum for the
exchange of national economic and social development views and
experiences," the ESCAP Secretariat said.
</P>
<P>
"The commission also acts as a regional body for
policy-oriented socio-economic research and analysis as well as an
executing agency of technical assistance," the secretariat said in
a press release issued today.
</P>
<P>
ESCAP now has grown to embrace 60 member and associate member
countries from an initial membership of 10 countries, representing
some 60 percent of the world's population, it said.
</P>
<P>
Adrianus Mooy, executive secretary of ESCAP, earlier this month
also noted: "the advent of the commission as an instrument to
assist in the reconstruction of war-torn areas must surely have
been a silver lining."
</P>
<P>
ESCAP was established on march 28, 1947, known as the economic
and social commission for Asia and the far east then. The name was
changed to ESCAP in 1977.
</P>
<P>
With the theme "50 years of achievement", the ESCAP is planning
to launch a series of activities, including a roving exhibition,
forums, visits to the ESCAP secretariat, and planting of a peace
pole in the U.N. conference center's garden here to mark its 50th
anniversary.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
