<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Boosting Express Transport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 28 (Xinhua) -- High speed is becoming a sign of
the times for China's highway, railway, and water transport
systems.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the Ministry of Communications show that China
now has 3,260 kilometers of expressways, compared with only 50 km
in the early 1990s. The combined length of high-grade highways,
with a designed speed of more than 80 km per hour, has reached
18,000 km.
</P>
<P>
Construction work on the country's first expressway, from
Shenyang to Dalian, in northeast China's Liaoning Province,
started in 1984.
</P>
<P>
An express railway from Beijing to Shanghai, two large cities
in China, will have a designed speed of 250 km per hour, 50 km
more than the lowest international express standard, making the
entire journey 6.5 hours long, revealed Zhou Yimin, deputy
director of the Beijing-Shanghai Expressway Research Office of the
Ministry of Railways.
</P>
<P>
The railway line will become one of the largest construction
projects for China in the next century, he said.
</P>
<P>
Though China has no express railways at present, trains on the
three major lines of Beijing-Guangzhou, Beijing-Shanghai, and
Beijing-Harbin will run at a per hour speed of 140 km as of next
week, sources say.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the country has a quasi-express railway line from
Guangzhou to Shenzhen, in southern Guangdong Province. Trains on
the line run at 160 km per hour.
</P>
<P>
The China State Shipbuilding Corporation says that more than
200 high performance vehicles are operating on over 70 water
routes in the country, covering the rivers of Zhujiang, Yangtze,
Huanghe (Yellow), and Heilongjiang, as well as Bohai Bay, the
Yellow Sea, the East China Sea, and the South China Sea.
</P>
<P>
The per hour speed of the ships reaches 60 to 70 km, above the
average travel speed of trains.
</P>
<P>
The Civil Aviation Administration of China predicts that
airplanes will carry 62 million passengers this year, a rise of
11.7 percent over 1996, and 38 planes will be added, bringing the
total number to 481.
</P>
<P>
Over the past three years, the number of air travelers has
grown at an average speed of 16.3 percent. Last year, the number
of travelers handled by airliners for the first time exceeded 50
million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970328.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kyrgyzstan to Seek Closer Ties With CIS States </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA-ATA, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Kyrgyz President Askar Akayev
said today that strengthening comprehensive cooperation with other
republics of the Commonwealth of Independent States will be one of
the priorities of Kyrgyzstan's foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the Supreme Council Wednesday, Akayev said the main
task of the Kyrgyz foreign policy is to constantly strengthen
bilateral and multilateral cooperation by which to create reliable
external conditions for national stability and security and
socio-economic development.
</P>
<P>
The president said Russia is Kyrgyzstan's major strategic
partner and their relations have seen positive development since
1991.
</P>
<P>
The cooperation within the Central Asia Alliance also made new
progress last year. The alliance's member states will seek more
cooperation in trade, waterpower, transportation and customs in
the future, Akayev said.
</P>
<P>
The alliance, established in July 1994, groups Uzbekistan,
Kyrgyzstan and Kazakhstan.
</P>
<P>
Akayev invited other countries to join the alliance as
observers and promised to make efforts to promote the alliance's
integration.
</P>
<P>
He said the confidence-building treaty signed by China, Russia,
Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan and Tajikistan in Shanghai last April and
the treaty on disarmament at the borders to be signed by the same
five countries in Moscow this April, will further deepen Kyrgyz
relations with China and benefit the two countries' cooperation in
other fields. 
</P>
