<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xiamen Promulgates New Measures on Overseas Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, March 28 (Xinhua) -- Xiamen, one of China's five
special economic zones, will provide overseas investors with eight
new preferential measures worked out recently.
</P>
<P>
Overseas companies, which have obtained approval after April 1,
1996 to invest in industrial and agricultural projects encouraged
by the Chinese government, and which will operate for more than 10
years, will be exempted from income tax in the first two years
after they make profits.
</P>
<P>
Those who invested in new and hi-tech projects since April 1,
1996 may get refunds from the taxes turned in to the state for
importing equipment for their own use.
</P>
<P>
Those who will invest more than 12 million US dollars in
Haicang, Xinglin, Jimei and Tong'an counties will be allowed to
pay land dues by installments within two years.
</P>
<P>
Investors who have opened three enterprises in China or input
30 million US dollars may set up investment companies, which can
be exempted from income tax in the first year of making profit.
</P>
<P>
Other preferential treatment concerned Chinese partners, staff
of overseas-funded firms and investors from Hong Kong, Macao and
Taiwan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
