<DOCNO> XIE19970328.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia-Singapore Bilateral Ties to Continue: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
 Deputy PM
</P>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, March 28 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Deputy Prime
Minister Anwar Ibrahim said today the Cabinet which met on
Wednesday decided that bilateral ties with Singapore will continue
but it will take time to restore the previous level of confidence.
</P>
<P>
The Cabinet regretted that some members of the Singapore
government "seem to lack insight and earnestness, even appear to
trivialize what is at issue," Anwar said in a statement issued
here today.
</P>
<P>
He said "the Cabinet in its meeting on Wednesday, March 26,
1997 discussed the events following the disparaging remarks on
Malaysia by Singapore's Senior Minister Lee Kuan Yew."
</P>
<P>
he said "the Cabinet feels, along with the Malaysian people,
that good neighborly relations are built upon the principle of
reciprocity, nurtured by mutual understanding and respect for one
another. We therefore regret that some members of the Singapore
government seem to lack in insight and earnestness, even appear to
trivialize what is at issue."
</P>
<P>
The Cabinet reaffirmed its decision of March 19, 1997, to
accept the apology tendered by Lee Kuan Yew and reaffirmed that
Malaysia seeks to normalize relations with Singapore, he said.
</P>
<P>
"However, such relations are a partnership. It is the quality
of the partnership that has been brought into question, naturally
it will take time and effort on both sides to re-establish
previous levels of confidence," he said.
</P>
<P>
This was the first statement by the Deputy Prime Minister who
chaired Wednesday's Cabinet meeting to clarify what exactly the
Cabinet decision was.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
