<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam's Economy Goes Well in First Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, March 28 (Xinhua) -- The economy of Vietnam has gone
well in the first three months of this year, an official report
said here today.
</P>
<P>
In the first quarter, the country's industrial output grew by
14 percent more than the same period last year and its import and
export turnover accounted for 20 and 20.6 percent of the yearly
plan respectively or a year-on-year increase of 22.5 and 10.7
percent, said the report.
</P>
<P>
More than 1.1 million hectares were put under winter-spring
rice in the northern provinces -- a 6 percent increase compared
with the same crop last year.
</P>
<P>
The disbursement for capital construction was 14.3 percent of
the yearly plan, an increase of 2.1 percent over the corresponding
period last year, and the prices of goods and services rose by 2.1
percent compared with december 1996, the lowest rate in the past
five years.
</P>
<P>
The government has granted licenses to 65 foreign-invested
projects with a total registered capital of 776.2 million
U.S. dollars by mid-March 1997, and signed a number of agreements
to the tune of 922.8 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970328.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan to Cut Taxes to Revive Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 28 (Xinhua) -- Finance Minister Sartaj Aziz
today announced a downward revision of tariffs, income tax and
general sales tax rates as part of an economic revival program.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made at the National Assembly during a
parliamentary meeting of the Pakistan Muslim League (N) which was
chaired by Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif.
</P>
<P>
The tax cuts had been done to revitalize the economy,
particularly the engine of growth of the industrial and export
sectors, the finance minister said.
</P>
<P>
The Economic Revival Program, Aziz said, had the potential of
taking Pakistan out of the current economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
"It is our own package and we are pleased that our new approach
package has been endorsed by the IMF (International Monetary Fund)
and will form the basis of negotiations on an ESAF (Extended
Structural Adjustment Facility) in the next few weeks," he added.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the maximum tariff was being reduced from the
present 65 percent to 45 percent, except for imports like
automobiles.
</P>
<P>
Describing the reform packages as "revolutionary steps," Aziz
said the number of tariff rates was being reduced from 13 to five.
</P>
<P>
The general sales tax (GST) would be cut from 18 percent to
12.5 percent. Items currently subject to 10 percent GST would
remain unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The package also included a drastic reduction in the personal
income tax and announcement of corporate income tax in advance for
public companies, other companies and banking companies for the
fiscal years 1997-98 and 1998-99.
</P>
<P>
The export enhancement package, a central pillar of the
government's program for economic recovery, is the strategy for
export-led growth, the finance minister said.
</P>
<P>
The government was setting a target of doubling the total
dollars value of exports in three years, said Aziz. Measures are
being taken to remove biases against exports by cutting duty on
import of machinery for export-oriented industries to 10 per cent.
</P>
<P>
Raw materials and machinery are to be made available to
exporters at international prices and raw materials used mainly
for export are being zero-rated, according to Aziz.
</P>
<P>
Duty drawback payments would be made within 14 days instead of
30 days at present. The government was revamping the 1981 export
houses scheme to facilitate export by small and medium-sized
enterprises, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
