<HEADLINE> Pakistan PM Vows to Root out Corruption, Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 28 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif today vowed to root out corruption and poverty in the
country, although these objectives cannot be achieved overnight.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a parliamentary meeting of the Pakistan Muslim
League (PML-N), Sharif urged party members to place confidence in
the economic revival program.
</P>
<P>
By implementing the program, Pakistan would be pulled out of
the current economic crunch which is evident in all spheres of
life, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Peace would return, and sectarianism would be controlled.
These are the problems which arise when people are faced with a
difficult economic situation.
</P>
<P>
"But these objectives would be achieved over a period of time
and not overnight. We would need full cooperation of our allied
parties to realize these goals," Sharif said.
</P>
<P>
He said he did not discriminate between the members of the
National Assembly and the Senate though the latter has no say in
passing the budget or in financial matters.
</P>
<P>
"But it will always be my endeavor to take the members of the
Senate into confidence before presenting such affairs before the
National Assembly," he added.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Sartaj Aziz later presented the economic
revival program which was approved by the meeting.  
</P>
</TEXT>
