<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Shows Deep Concern for Middle East Situation: FM Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 28 (Xinhua) -- Foreign Ministry Spokesman Cui
Tiankai said here today that China is deeply concerned about the
difficult situation in the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Cui said that Israel, disregarding the opposition from the Arab
nations and the international community, has recently insisted on
the establishment of Jewish settlement in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the Israeli conduct "has brought about
increasing tensions in the Palestine-Israel relations and more
violence," and the peace process is now "faced with difficulty."
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese Government is deeply concerned and worried about
the Middle East peace process," Cui noted.
</P>
<P>
Cui said the Chinese government has all along actively backed
the Middle East peace process. It holds that all the parties
concerned should abide by the related UN resolutions, and seek a
fair and reasonable solution to the Middle East issue at an early
date through political negotiations and in the spirit of "land for
peace," Cui said.
</P>
<P>
"This is not only in the fundamental interests of the peoples
of the Middle East countries," the spokesman said, "but also
conducive to peace, stability and development of the region and
the world as a whole."
</P>
<P>
"In order to create a favorable atmosphere for the continuous
development of the peace process, we demand the Israeli Government
cancel the plan to expand the Jewish settlement in East Jerusalem,
and all the parties concerned earnestly carry out the agreements
that have been reached," Cui stressed.
</P>
<P>
He said that China, as a permanent member of the UN Security
Council, is willing to work with the international community to
deliver thorough, fair peace in the Middle East at an early date.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
