<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-Canadian School Provides Opportunities for Cultural Exchanges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 28 (Xinhua) -- A high school to offer both
Chinese and western-style courses will open this fall in the
Chinese capital, enabling students to experience differences
between the two cultures.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing Concord College of Sino-Canada plans to include in
its curriculum not only Chinese and other subjects provided in
ordinary Chinese high schools, but also computer science, arts and
Canadian history, both in Chinese and English.
</P>
<P>
The school, the first of its kind in Beijing, is scheduled to
open in September, when it has both Chinese and Canadian teachers
and students in the classrooms together.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice-Premier Li Lanqing and Canadian Prime Minister
Jean Chretien recently conveyed their congratulations to the
establishment of the school.
</P>
<P>
"I expect the school to play a new role in promoting
educational and cultural exchanges between two countries," said
Lan Weimin, who is in charge of the establishment of the school.
</P>
<P>
The school was jointly launched by the Experimental High School
affiliated to Beijing Normal University, the Advanced Education
and Labor Department, N.B., Canada, and AKD International Inc., an
investment group.
</P>
<P>
"We'll offer courses mainly in line with China's education
outline, while still following some useful practices of the
Canadian education system," Lan said.
</P>
<P>
In the school, located in Beijing's suburban Tongxian County,
students will also undertake eight-month or two-year vocational
education after they complete their three-year high school studies.
</P>
<P>
And they will be granted mutually-recognized Chinese and
Canadian diplomas, Lan said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
