<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian, S. Koreans Win 1,500 Meters in Nagano </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, March 28 (Xinhua) -- South Korean Chun Lee-Kyung and
Canadian Marc Gagnon displayed their top forms as defending
overall champions by winning their 1,500 meters at the World Short
Track Speedskating Championships in Nagano on Friday.
</P>
<P>
As the championships raised the curtains, Chun, seeking her
third straight world title, outpaced teammate Won Hye-Kyung to win
the women's 1,500-meter final in two minutes 29.42 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Won clocked 2:29.55 for the second, followed by China's Yang
Yang of Heilongjiang province in 2:30.46.
</P>
<P>
The men's 1,500m title went to Gagnon who led most of the way,
beating off a strong challenge from Orazio Fagone of Italy to win
in 2:21.32.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian won the same event at the world championships in
Hague last year in a world record time of 2:18.16.
</P>
<P>
Fagone finished second in 2:21.61, ahead of teammate Mirko
Vuillermin in 2:22.06.
</P>
<P>
Kim Dong-Sung of South Korea, who took the lead from Gagnon at
one stage, was disqualified for impeding.
</P>
<P>
The winner received five points, the runner-up three, third
placer two and fourth placer one point, counting towards the
individual overall championships decided over four distances.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
