<DOCNO> XIE19970328.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 3.9 Million People Need Food in Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 28 (Xinhua) -- The primary food shortage
findings by the World Food Program (WFP) has revealed that food
scarcity in Tanzania is more serious than it was reported earlier
by the government, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The WFP representative here, Irene Lacy told Minister for
Agriculture and Cooperatives Paul Kimiti here on Wednesday that
3.9 million people need food in one way or another while the
early report indicated only 670,000 people.
</P>
<P>
Lacy said the selected committee which visited 12 regions
found out that while some people could buy the food, it was not
available; there were also those who could not afford to buy the
food but could work for it, and there were those who cound'nt do
both and needed emergency food.
</P>
<P>
She said among the 12 regions visited, 11 regions needed the
food support immediately and the Arusha and Lindi regions were
considered to be more critical than the rest.
</P>
<P>
The total relief food requirement is estimated at 30,000 tons
of maize and 3,000 tons of beans, she said, warning that high
food prices in the regions are causing severe hardships to the
people and that efforts are needed to encourage traders to
release maize at reasonable price in order to establish market
peace for both maize and beans.
</P>
<P>
Responding to the report, Kimiti said the government has
stocks of maize ready to be sent to the markets but there is no
fund to deliver the food.
</P>
<P>
The 12 regions visited by the selected committee are Arusha,
Mwanza, Mara, Shinyanga, Kilimanjaro, Tanga, Mtwara, Lindi,
Singida, Dodoma, Tabora and Morogoro. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
