<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Announces Deregulation Measures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, March 28 (Xinhua) -- Japan announced Friday a package
of revised measures to deregulate rules which are blamed for
preventing a vigorous expansion of the economy and the creation of
new business.
</P>
<P>
The revised package is the final installment of a three-year
program containing 2,823 measures to deregulate areas such as
financial services, communications, housing, distribution,
transport, energy, labor and education.
</P>
<P>
Foreign and domestic businesses complain that red tape in
Japan has been suffocating the economy.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto has said that his
government is committed to cutting red tape to boost the fragile
economy because it is making Japan less attractive to investors.
</P>
<P>
Of the 2,823 measures, only 890 are new. The rest have been
invoked in some form by government departments.
</P>
<P>
Included in the revised package are measures to ease rules on
foreign currency transactions in Tokyo and in Japanese stock
markets.
</P>
<P>
Under the package, financial institutions will be allowed to
set up branches wherever they wish, and stockbroking fees will be
liberalized.
</P>
<P>
And the package will permit construction of higher buildings
in city areas to create more living space, loosen rules on private
job agencies and allow firms to enter Japan's telecoms market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
