<HEADLINE> Turkey to Buy Vessels to Strengthen Coast Defense </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, March 28 (Xinhua) -- Turkey plans to spend about 250
million U.S. dollars on purchasing a large number of patrol boats
and navy helicopters in an effort to strengthen its coast
defense.
</P>
<P>
Local newspaper Daily News today quoted military sources as
saying that the proposals for buying six speedboats were being
studied by Turkey's Undersecretariat for Defense Industries (SSM).
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Turkey has a plan to import 14 large coast guard
vessels, according to the unidentified sources.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that Turkey also intends to jointly produce
such boats with a foreign company in one of the Turkish
shipyards. However, it fell short of mentioning the shipyard by
name.
</P>
<P>
The sources told the paper that a number of navy helicopters
would be bought in order to provide air support for the vessels,
adding some foreign firms had presented their proposals to the
SSM.
</P>
<P>
According to these sources, Sikorsky's S-76 model, Eurocopter's
Dolphin and Augusta-Bell's helicopter are highly competitive for
the deal.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Coast Guard has long been handicapped by a lack of
well equipped boats to patrol Turkey's vast territorial waters
against increasingly rampant smuggling of illegal immigrants and
drugs.
</P>
<P>
The latest series of arms deals are expected to help solve
this long-standing problem, sources added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
