<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indo-Pak Foreign Secretary-Level Dialogue Begins Today </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 28 (Xinhua) -- Foreign secretaries of India
and Pakistan are resuming their dialogue here today, stalled since
January 1994, in a bid to normalize their relations.
</P>
<P>
The formal inaugural session is expected to start at Hyderabad
House, a state guest house, here this afternoon. Prior to the
dialogue, Pakistani Foreign Secretary Shamshad Ahmad will call on
Indian External Affairs Minister I. K. Gujral at his office.
</P>
<P>
There will be no formal agenda for the dialogue. Both India and
Pakistan have expressed their desire to improve their relations
through peaceful talks.
</P>
<P>
In a written statement released to the press on his arrival
here Thursday evening for the four-day dialogue, Ahmad said, "It
is our belief that given the political will on the part of the
leadership of our two countries, time is propitious for us to
seize this opportunity for removing the root causes of tension
between India and Pakistan."
</P>
<P>
Talking to newsmen at the airport, Ahmad said he looked forward
to "substantive and meaningful discussions" with his counterpart
Salman Haider. He said it was Pakistan's belief that determined
efforts must be made by the two countries to rid South Asia of the
existing tensions and hostilities.
</P>
<P>
Greeting his Pakistani counterpart at the airport, Indian
Foreign Secretary Salman Haider said, "We know there is a great
deal of expectations on both sides...We hope to engage ourselves
in a purposeful and constructive dialogue."
</P>
<P>
Since last year, political leaders of the two countries have
time and again expressed their desire and willingness to resume
their talks so as to normalize their tense relations and enhance
their exchange and cooperation in various fields.
</P>
<P>
Since winning independence from Britain in 1947, India and
Pakistan have fought three wars, two of them over Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
Now leaders of the two countries are beginning to realize that
the conflicts between them have drained the treasury and wasted
enormous manpower and resources and that the most pressing thing
to do is to solve their long-standing disputes through peaceful
talks so as to concentrate their efforts on economic development
and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The resumption of Indo-Pakistani dialogue has been widely
welcomed by the people of India and Pakistan as well as by the
international community, and the move is generally perceived as
the best chance in three years to reduce tension in the region.
</P>
<P>
"We have wasted more than five decades in animosities. The end
result is that those countries which were far behind us when
freedom came have gone ahead," Gujral said on the eve of the
talks.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970328.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> a City in the Air </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, March 28 (Xinhua) -- At first glance, Chongqing, the
new and largest municipality of China, may remind visitors of a
beautiful castle in the sky.
</P>
<P>
This is not only because this city of southwest China is built
almost entirely on hills, but also because of its modern
atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
While in the past, wooden houses dominated the city scene,
tall, modern commercial and residential buildings now dot the
slopes, forming a skyline that can be seen in many other booming
cities in China.
</P>
<P>
Upon closer inspection, flower and vegetable gardens can be
seen on the rooftops of many buildings -- an innovative way of
solving the land shortage that adds a bright spot of vitality to
this industrial city of over 10 million people.
</P>
<P>
Chongqing this month was separated from Sichuan Province to
become China's fourth municipality directly under the central
government. The total population of the municipality is over 30
million.
</P>
<P>
A modern sports ground for the Chongqing No. 29 Middle School
was built on the roof of a neighboring department store to end the
constant need to borrow sports areas for the students. The "sports
ground in the air" has three standard basketball courts, a track,
and a gymnasium.
</P>
<P>
The city also has traffic in the sky: apart from buses running
on the winding roads through the hills, transportation services --
which themselves have attracted thousands of tourists -- include
two aerial cable cars stretching across the Yangtze and Jialing
rivers which run through the city.
</P>
<P>
To appreciate the view from above at night, Chongqing people
suggest a trip to the top of Piba Hill, a local favorite, or a
visit to the Wudu Hotel where a tea house on its 24-story roof has
been built to serve night-viewers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970328.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mountainous Chongqing Features Unique Transportation Options </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, March 28 (Xinhua) -- Before arriving in Chongqing
for the first time, Ms. Yang of Shanghai imagined travel in this
mountain city would be difficult.
</P>
<P>
But soon she was thoroughly charmed by the unique and
convenient transportation services the city has to offer, and has
joined the growing multitude of visitors who feel traveling in
Chongqing is a special treat rather than a nuisance.
</P>
<P>
People leaving the Chongqing Railway Station no longer have to
climb up high stone steps to get to a street leading to the city
center -- a modern outdoor escalator now lifts passengers there in
just two and a half minutes.
</P>
<P>
"It not only saves me a great deal of walking, but also serves
as a good way to sightsee," commented one traveler.
</P>
<P>
With a length of 112 meters and a slope of 30 degrees, the 150
million US dollar moving stairs are the longest of the kind over
hilly land in Asia.
</P>
<P>
Operational on February 18, 1996, the outdoor escalator not
only is a convenience for tourists who want to go to many tourist
attractions and the major commercial centers, but is also liked by
local residents.
</P>
<P>
Chongqing, which this month was separated from Sichuan Province
to become China's largest municipality, is known to have one of
the hilliest topographical areas among large Chinese cities. But
unique travel opportunities are not limited to the
mountains: cross-river traffic on the Yangtze River and the
Jialing River running through the city is also diversified, as
people can choose between a ferry, an aerial cable or a cable car
to get back and forth.
</P>
<P>
The aerial cable across the Jialing River, which was put into
use in January of 1982, is the first large passenger in-air
cableway in China.
</P>
<P>
With a length of 714 meters, and two cars each capable of
holding 50 people, the cable transports an average of 10,000
people daily.
</P>
<P>
The Chongqing section of the Yangtze River had its first such
suspended cable in 1987. At 1,166 meters long, the cableway has
two 80-passenger cars running dozens of meters high above the
river.
</P>
<P>
At the Chaotianmen Dock of the Yangtze River, a 140-meter cable
car has been running since 1984, taking passengers up to a slope
of 36 degrees to reach major streets. The price is a meagre two
jiao (0.20 yuan) -- a fraction of a penny -- per passenger.
</P>
<P>
Several such riverside cable cars are now in service.
</P>
<P>
Though Chongqing city proper has a population of over 10
million, its population of bicycle riders is the smallest among
large Chinese cities. However, it has no lack of modern means of
transport, such as buses, taxis, and minibuses.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970328.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Municipality to Build Grand Square </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, March 28 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Chongqing has
started to construct a grand square, the first key infrastructure
item after the city was named the country's fourth municipality
directly under the central government.
</P>
<P>
The new project, the People's Square, includes the construction
of a 24,000-square-meter square and the renovation of the People's
Hall. It is scheduled to be completed on May 31.
</P>
<P>
Once finished, the square and hall will be the main public
gathering places for the local political and cultural activities.
</P>
<P>
The People's Square will be composed of three parts: the
granite-paved central space covering a T-shaped area of 7,000
square meters; the cultural space that includes a performing
platform and a rest area; and a grassland region with artificial
fountains and streams.
</P>
<P>
The People's Hall was built in 1951, but now is in need of
repair.
</P>
<P>
Chongqing residents have donated over three million yuan (about
357,100 US dollars) for the project. 
</P>
</TEXT>
