<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam's Inflation Falls to Lowest Level Since 1991 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, March 28 (Xinhua) -- Prices for services and goods in
Vietnam rose by 2.1 percent in the first three months of the year,
the lowest since 1991, Vietnam's General Department of Statistics
reported.
</P>
<P>
Prices for food increased by 0.7 percent and services by 4.8
percent. Gold prices decreased by 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The country's industries grossed 2.66 billion U.S.dollars in
the first quarter of this year, an increase of 14 percent over
the same period last year, with the state-owned sector up by 12.5
percent, non-state sector by 10.8 percent and foreign-invested
sector by 20.7 percent, it said.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's exports earned about 1.79 billion dollars during this
period, representing an increase of 22.5 percent compared with the
same period of last year. Its import turnover reached 2.72 billion
dollars, 10 percent higher than the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The report forecasts increases in prices in the coming months
due to a 20 percent increase in salaries and a rise in the value
of the dollar against the Vietnamese dong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970328.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seles Sails into Lipton Final against Hingis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 28 (Xinhua) -- Monica Seles looked like the
Seles of old Thursday night when she sailing into the final of the
Lipton Championships, where she will meet Martina Hingis in a
showdown of once and future world number ones.
</P>
<P>
The fourth-seeded Seles, playing her first tournament of the
year after being sidelined by a broken finger, destroyed
11th-seeded Austrian Barbara Paulus 6-1, 6-0 in 51 minutes to take
her place in the final.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Thursday, Swiss teen sensation Hingis won a hard-fought
battle with third-seeded Czech veteran Jana Novotna 6-3, 2-6, 6-4
to stretch her perfect 1997 record to 25-0.
</P>
<P>
The 16-year-old Hingis, who Monday will become the youngest
player ever ranked number one in the world, will be looking for
her fifth title of the year when she faces former number one Seles
on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Seles, who was 17 when she first grabbed the top ranking six
years ago, held the previous record for youngest world number one.
</P>
<P>
The 14th-ranked Paulus and Seles were tied 1-1 in the first set
when the Yugoslav-born American pushed her game into high gear and
raced through the next 11 games without dropping another one to
the helpless Austrian. 
</P>
</TEXT>
