<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Everton Drops Bid for Norwegian Players </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Everton withdrew their 3 million
pound (4.9 million US dollars) bid for two Norwegian players on
Thursday as the club was left reeling by the departure of manager
Joe Royle.
</P>
<P>
Norwegian side Brann Bergen on Wednesday rejected an offer of
2.5 million pounds for midfielder Claus Eftevaag and striker Tore
Andre Flo.
</P>
<P>
Everton came back with an increased offer but then withdrew it
three hours before Thursday's English league transfer deadline.
</P>
<P>
Shortly afterwards Royle announced he was to leave the club "by
mutual consent."
</P>
<P>
The two players had come to Royle's attention during their
team's European Cup Winners' Cup quarter-final against Everton's
neighbours and great rivals Liverpool. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970328.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Writers Say Good-bye to Iron Bowl </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, March 28 (Xinhua) -- More Chinese writers have
forsaken the "iron bowl" system -- the former Soviet model under
which the state subsidizes writers for their entire life.
</P>
<P>
A contract system has been introduced into the literary circle,
mandating that a writer has to sign a contract with a literary
organization to obtain financial aid, sources said.
</P>
<P>
These organizations pay salaries or subsidies to the working
writers, but if the writers do not produce work, they will be
dismissed.
</P>
<P>
There are thousands of writers' associations and arts societies
at different levels in China, a country that holds a sacred view
of culture and literature. Writing novels is a government-subsided
profession for many members of these associations.
</P>
<P>
The former system has come under fire by some critics who
believe it benefits lazy people: a writer can become famous
overnight for one short story, then can stop writing and live off
his short-lived success for the rest of his life.
</P>
<P>
The new system, although still regarded by some writers as a
"mud bowl" because it does not guarantee true freedom for writers,
is a sign of progress as it introduces competition, said Ji
Wenzhang, a writer.
</P>
<P>
The Hebei Literary Institute has signed agreements with 43
contracted writers in the past few years. Only half of them were
re-employeed when the contracts reached their terms.
</P>
<P>
Guan Renshan, a novelist, said that the new system forced him
to continue to write good works. "In the past, no matter if I
wrote or not, I received regular government payment. But now if I
stop writing, I will lag behind."
</P>
<P>
Many people agree that some booming coastal provinces are the
birthplaces of the contract-writer system.
</P>
<P>
As book remuneration is still very low in many cases, many
writers will have to depend on salaries given by literary
associations, while others have to write books in their spare time
and receive regular salaries from their work units.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970328.0167 </DOCNO>
