<HEADLINE> OSCE Agrees to Send Protection Force for Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, March 27 (Xinhua) -- The Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) announced today that it has agreed
to send a multinational force to Albania, but will seek
endorsement for this from the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Austria press Agentur reported that the decision was made at a
meeting of the OSCE permanent council.
</P>
<P>
The aim of the force is to create a secure environment for
international aid organizations working in the crisis-ridden
Balkan nation, and help prepare for the general elections due by
June.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the OSCE said the planned foreign protection
force, which will consist of 2,500 personnel and could be extended
to 5,000 if the security situation deteriorates, will stay in
Albania until its general election is over.
</P>
<P>
The OSCE said it expected that states willing to participate in
an Albanian protection force would act "in accordance with the
United Nations Charter and OSCE principles, and in accordance with
the appropriate action by the U.N.Security Council."
</P>
<P>
Several countries including Italy, Greece, France, Spain and
Portugal have offered to send troops. 
</P>
</TEXT>
