<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Commission Concludes Annual Session on Narcotics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, March 27 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Commission on
Narcotic Drugs ended its annual session here today after deciding
on institutional buildup for fighting illegal drugs.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, the 40th of its kind, called for strengthening the
U.N. International Drug Control Program to ensure the
implementation of measures designed against narcotics.
</P>
<P>
It also approved 14 annual reports and related resolutions
submitted by the program and the U.N. International Narcotics
Control Board, including one on amphetamine-type stimulants.
</P>
<P>
As a focus of the session, the resolution on amphetamines urged
the international community and governments worldwide to cooperate
and coordinate their efforts to crack down on the synthetic drugs.
</P>
<P>
The illegal manufacturing, trafficking and abuse of
amphetamine-type stimulants and their chemical precursors could
pose a major threat in the next century, experts warned.
</P>
<P>
Members of the U.N. commission also agreed on the timetable and
agenda of the next preparatory meeting for a U.N. special
conference on drugs scheduled to open next year.
</P>
<P>
The agenda would include the preparation of a declaration to be
released at the end of the conference calling for political
commitment from world leaders to fighting illegal drugs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
