<HEADLINE> Canada's Stock Exchanges Post Heavy Loss </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Canada's Toronto Stock Exchange
(TSE) today nose-dived nearly 200 points to post its biggest loss
in almost a decade.
</P>
<P>
The TSE 300 composite index lost 191.09 points to close at
5,931.75, the worst single-day loss since the collapse of the
North American stock markets in October 1987.
</P>
<P>
The TSE loss was followed by drops in three other stock markets
across the country.
</P>
<P>
The exchanges of Alberta, Vancouver and Montreal fell today by
3 percent, 4.7 percent and 3 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
The stock market freefall was triggered by the dumping of
almost 8 million shares of the troubled Bre-X Minerals Co. Ltd.
</P>
<P>
The mining company resumed trading after a one-day suspension
during which it revealed its Indonesian gold mine could turn out
to be bust.
</P>
<P>
Bre-X lost 2.8 billion Canadian dollars (2.0 billion
U.S. dollars) in value as its shares fell from 15.50 dollars (11.3
dollars) to 2.5 dollars (1.8 dollars) in a matter of minutes,
dragging the company down with them.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian market was also hit by the fall on the Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
The Dow industrial average suffered its eighth-worst point
drop, falling 140.11 to 6,740,59, when the latest statistics
showed that the U.S. economy continues to grow vigorously. 
</P>
</TEXT>
