<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Consumer Prices Drop 0.2 percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, March 28 (Xinhua -- Japan's consumer price index in
February fell 0.2 percent from the previous month, but was up 0.6
percent on the same month a year earlier, the Management and
Coordination Agency announced Friday.
</P>
<P>
The month-to-month decline followed a 0.1 percent drop in
January.
</P>
<P>
The rise on a yearly basis was due partly to price rises in
fresh fruit and fish, rents and school tuition fees, the agency
said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the consumer price index in Tokyo, a leading
indicator of nationwide inflation, rose 0.1 percent from February
but was unchanged from a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
For fiscal 1996 ending March 31, consumer prices in Tokyo were
up 0.1 percent from the previous year, after falling 0.4 percent
in fiscal 1995, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
Fiscal 1995 marked the drop of Tokyo's consumer price index
from year-before levels since the agency began to compile the
index in 1971.
</P>
<P>
In fiscal 1996, food prices rose 0.2 percent following a fall
of 1.5 percent a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Clothing and shoe prices were up 0.3 percent after being flat
the previous year, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
The price of educational services rose 2.6 percent in fiscal
1996 after rising 2.2 percent a year earlier, while prices of
furniture and household products fell 3.0 percent following a
fall of 2.0 percent a year earlier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970328.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Population Stands at 125 Million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, March 28 (Xinhua) -- Statistics published by Japan's
Management and Coordination Agency Thursday show that Japan had a
population of 125.86 million by the end of October, 1996, an
increase of only 0.23 percent over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The population within the 15 to 64 years age group stands at
87.16 million, decreasing by about 100,000 from a year ago, a
movement unprecedented in Japan since World War II.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the population under the age of 14 dwindled by
350,000 to 19.69 million, reflecting a growing trend in Japan of
marrying at a mature age and bearing fewer children.
</P>
<P>
Figures provided by Metropolitan Tokyo show the city's
population reached 11.602,642 at the end of 1997, increasing by
14,916 over the same period last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
