<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Defense Secretary Defends Missile Accord With Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 27 (Xinhua) -- United States Defense
Secretary William Cohen today defended the missile agreement
reached by U.S. President Bill Clinton and Russian President Boris
Yeltsin last week in Helsinki.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a Navy League convention here, Cohen said that
Clinton gave up nothing by agreeing with Russia to ban space-based
theater missile defense systems.
</P>
<P>
In the joint statement, Clinton and Yeltsin reaffirmed the 1972
Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty, agreeing to share details of their
theater missile defenses, and restrict development of theater
defenses that could be based in space.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was criticized by some lawmakers as a giveaway
that will place lives of Americans in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
Cohen argued that any space-based system that could protect
troops in a military theater could also be used to shoot down an
intercontinental ballistic missile aimed at the U.S., and such
systems are banned by the treaty.
</P>
<P>
"So this provision has given up nothing," he said. "It simply
confirms the fact of where we are today." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
