<HEADLINE> Ukraine Seeks Compromise on Black Sea Fleet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma
said here today that necessary conditions must be created for
normal operations of Russia's Black Sea Fleet in the Black Sea and
Crimea.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference, Kuchma proposed seeking a compromise on
the issue, and said his country was ready to reach a compromise.
</P>
<P>
The Black Sea Fleet, a major part of the former Soviet Union's
naval force, is based on the Ukrainian peninsula of Crimea. Russia
and Ukraine both claimed the fleet after the disintegration of the
Soviet Union in 1991.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have reached a tentative agreement on
dividing the fleet, but there have been disputes over the status
of Sevastopol, the headquarters of the fleet.
</P>
<P>
Russian President Boris Yeltsin will seek crucial ways to
resolve the dispute between Russia and Ukraine, the Ukrainian
president said.
</P>
<P>
Kuchma also stressed that the two countries must sign
agreements on bilateral relations in the near future.
</P>
<P>
He said Kiev wanted to see greater cooperation with the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) under the Partnership for
Peace Program, but would not apply for a NATO membership at
present.
</P>
<P>
"It would be quite laughable if Ukraine said 'we want to join
NATO today,'" he told the press conference.
</P>
<P>
The Ukrainian president is in Moscow to attend a summit of the
12-nation Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS) scheduled to be
held Friday. The summit, bringing together the leaders of the
former Soviet republics except the three Baltic states, is to be
chaired by Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, heads of government of the member states met to
prepare for the summit, which will focus on a framework for
economic integration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
