<HEADLINE> East Chinese Province Develops Export-Oriented Agriculture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, March 28 (Xinhua) -- Export-oriented agriculture in
east China's coastal province of Fujian has become a major
contributor to its economic development.
</P>
<P>
The province exported 3.38 billion US dollars worth of farm
products in 1995, accounting for 36 percent of its total exports,
says Liu Qinrui, the director of the Provincial Agriculture Office.
</P>
<P>
Fujian Province adopted policies in the early 1980s to
encourage overseas investment in its hilly areas, and the influx
of foreign funds contributed greatly to its forest cover
percentage, and outputs of longan and litchi, which rank first
in China.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1990s the province has invited more overseas
participation in comprehensive agriculture development, involving
processing, storage, farm machinery, water conservancy, power
plants, and other infrastructural facilities.
</P>
<P>
The province has imported 2,700 improved strains of seed, 4,000
items of advanced technology and equipment, in an effort to
modernize its agriculture, the official says.
</P>
<P>
More than 3,200 overseas-funded enterprises have by now
invested two billion US dollars into agriculture-related
industries.
</P>
<P>
An American company has invested in producing the famous oolong
tea in Zhangpu County and raised the purchase price to
10 to 12 yuan from one to two yuan per kilogram. Local tea
growers' per capita annual income rocketed to 5,000 yuan from 500
yuan.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan plays a major part in Fujian's export-oriented
agriculture. Nearly half the overseas-funded enterprises and used
capital come from Taiwan. The two partners co-established in
Xiamen the Fujian-Taiwan Agricultural High-Technology Park.
enditem



nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
