<HEADLINE> European Experts Meet Albanian Leaders on Relief Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Albanian Prime Minister Bashkim
Fino renewed his country's request today for a multinational force
to secure humanitarian aid.
</P>
<P>
During talks with a 15-member European delegation of the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE), the
European Union (EU) and its Commission, Fino said security in
Albania was improving slowly, but a protection force was necessary
to secure safe transport and distribution of relief materials.
</P>
<P>
Fino stressed that a security force is especially needed at the
capital international airport, the port of Durres west of Tirana
and the Vlora port in the south, and along key roads.
</P>
<P>
Albania has been plunged into a lawlessness since January when
nation-wide protests broke out in protests of collapsed investment
schemes.
</P>
<P>
The protests later mushroomed into armed unrest in the south.
</P>
<P>
So far the OSCE has agreed to set up a security force in
principle, but the member states failed to approve a mandate for a
military mission at a meeting in Vienna Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Some member states said the United Nations Security Council
should set out the mission's mandate.
</P>
<P>
It was unclear when the OSCE would meet again.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, the European delegation also met with Albanian
Interior Minister Belul Cela and Defense Minister Shaqir
Vukaj. Cela requested the OSCE and EU provide special equipment
needed by police and anti-terrorist special force.
</P>
<P>
Vukaj said the country's heavy equipment, including aircraft
and armored vehicles, was still under control of the army.
</P>
<P>
He added that the army was being regrouped and a special force
was being formed to help gain control of the airports, sea ports
and roads.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, trucks sent by the Geneva-based International
Committee of the Red Cross carrying international emergency food
aid to Albania stopped at the Greek border Thursday, waiting for
word from relief workers on the other side that it was safe to
cross.
</P>
<P>
The trucks would try to cross the border on Friday and hoped to
make their way to the port of Durres, dropping off food in towns
along the way, reports said. 
</P>
