<HEADLINE> Bulgaria to Raise Wages Next Month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Bulgarian Minister of Labour and
Social Welfare Ivan Neikov announced here today that from April 1,
wages coming within the framework of the budget would be raised by
70 percent on average, nationwide.
</P>
<P>
He told a press conference that salaries of teachers, doctors,
cultural workers and servicemen from the Defense and Interior
Ministries would be raised by this amount.
</P>
<P>
From April 1, the minimum monthly wage would stand at 29,920
leva (19 U.S. dollars). Cultural workers would get a monthly pay
of 72,479 leva (46 dollars) and doctors 142,380 leva (90
dollars). Monthly subsidies for children would be raised to 6,190
leva (4 dollars).
</P>
<P>
The government decided Wednesday that starting on April 1,
retirees would get an extra pension of 20,000 leva (13 dollars),
with the highest reaching 42,120 leva (26 dollars).
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria will lift almost all price restrictions by the end of
May, with those of electricity, heating power and fuel reaching or
nearing the international level. The move is under an agreement
reached with the International Monetary Fund. 
</P>
