<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO: No Definite Link Yet Between Madcow Disease and CJD </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, March 27 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization
(WHO) today reiterated that there still has been no definite link
between the madcow disease and its human equivalent.
</P>
<P>
WHO made the statement in its guidelines for avoiding the
madcow disease, formally known as bovine spongiform encephalopathy
(BSE), in making medical products of human and animal origins.
</P>
<P>
There has been "no link definitely established" between BSE and
its human variant form of Creutzfeldt-Jakob Disease (CJD), said
the United Nations specialized agency headquartered here.
</P>
<P>
The guidelines were published after a WHO-sponsored
international consultation from March 24 to 26, or a year after
BSE's possible link with CJD sent a shock wave across Europe.
</P>
<P>
During the consultation, experts confirmed their previous
conclusions and statements on transmissible spongiform
encephalopathies (TSE), including the need for continued and
intensified research.
</P>
<P>
They also concluded that new information does not change
previous recommendations regarding milk and gelatin safety.
</P>
<P>
WHO recommended, however, that cattle sources and other animal
species naturally affected by a TSE should be avoided whenever
possible for preparing medicinal products and devices.
</P>
<P>
When cattle sources are unavoidable, the world's top health
agency said, source countries should be those which have low or no
BSE confirmed by an effective surveillance system.
</P>
<P>
The guidelines should also be applied to medical products from
other animal species with naturally-acquired TSE, WHO said.
</P>
<P>
Although there has been no proven or even probable instance of
CJD transmission from human to human by blood transfusion or blood
products, observation must continue, it said.
</P>
<P>
Experts associated with WHO concluded that blood transfusions
continue to be safe, but organ transplant donors should exclude
individuals who are at risk of CJD and other familial TSE.
</P>
<P>
WHO said that it will follow the development of the situation
and take into consideration any new element that could modify or
change its conclusions and recommendations regarding the matter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970328.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-28 </DATE_TIME>
