<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chronology of Peru Hostage Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, March 27 (Xinhua) -- The Lima hostage crisis hit the
100-day mark today and following is a chronology of the main
events of the crisis:
</P>
<P>
Dec. 17, 1996 -- Some 20 heavily armed rebels captured hundreds
of guests of the Japanese ambassador in his residence but they
freed all women and some elderly men soon after the attack.
</P>
<P>
Dec. 18 -- The rebels threatened to kill their hostages unless
the Peruvian government frees about 400 jailed comrades.
</P>
<P>
Dec. 19 -- Four ambassadors were released to be a
"communications channel" between the rebels and the government.
</P>
<P>
Dec. 20 -- Rebels freed 38 hostages.
</P>
<P>
Dec. 22 -- Rebels freed 225 hostages not linked to the
government.
</P>
<P>
Dec. 28 -- Government negotiator Domingo Palermo entered the
residence for face-to-face negotiations with the rebels. The
rebels released 20 hostages.
</P>
<P>
Jan. 1, 1997 -- Rebels released seven captives, lowering
hostage total to 74.
</P>
<P>
Feb. 1 -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto and
Fujimori met in Toronto. The two agreed to push for direct talks
with rebels.
</P>
<P>
Feb. 11 -- Talks restarted in a safe house opposite the
ambassador's residence.
</P>
<P>
Feb. 17 -- Sixty-second day of standoff, beating Latin
America's previous longest hostage siege: a 61-day seizure of the
Dominican Embassy in 1980.
</P>
<P>
March 3 -- Fujimori made a surprise trip to Cuba where
President Fidel Castro offered to grant asylum to rebels if all
sides agreed.
</P>
<P>
March 5 -- Ninth round of talks was held where the two sides
exchanged formal proposals.
</P>
<P>
March 18-20 -- Japan's Vice-Foreign Minister Masahiko Komura
visited Peru, Cuba and the Dominican Republic. He received formal
agreements from Havana and Santo Domingo to give the
hostage-takers asylum. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970328.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bamerindus Could Become Biggest Bank in Latin America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Brazil's Bamerindus Bank,
which has been taken over by the Hong Kong Shanghai Banking
Corporation (HSBC) British bank, could become the biggest bank in
Latin America.
</P>
<P>
"HSBC will be the biggest foreign bank in the region, and HSBC
Bamerindus the biggest bank of Latin America," said Michael
Geoghegan, who will be the president of the new entity.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank of Brazil determined Wednesday this week to
sell Bamerindus -- the fifth biggest private financial institution
in Brazil -- to the HSBC, which must assume administration of the
HSBC Bamerindus next Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Bamerindus Bank has 1,241 agencies throughout Brazil and
three abroad; a portfolio of 2,630,238 clients, and a
23,000-employee payroll.
</P>
<P>
The British bank, founded in 1865 in Hong Kong and in London,
and considered by the The Banker magazine to be the biggest bank
in the world, acquired the almost 10 billion dollars worth of
assets and liabilities of Bamerindus in exchange for an investment
of just 1 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The commitment also involved assuming a great part of the
Brazilian institution's deficit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
