<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Bosnian Refugees Return Home From Germany </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, March 27 (Xinhua) -- About 100 Bosnian refugees
repatriated by Germany today arrived in Sarajevo, capital of
Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
Some 100,000 Bosnian refugees are expected to be repatriated
home from Germany by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
Bosnia reached a repatriation agreement with Germany in 1995 to
send back roughly 320,000 Bosnian refugees now staying in Germany.
</P>
<P>
The repatriated refugees will, it is believed, worsen the
unemployment in the country in which 350,000 are now jobless.
</P>
<P>
More than 320,000 refugees fled to Germany after the
disintegration of former Yugoslavia in 1991. Bonn said it spent
about 500 million marks (350 million U.S. dollars) a year to feed
the Bosnian refugees taken in by Germany's 16 regional states.
</P>
<P>
Facing budget crisis after the Bosnian war ended at the end of
1995, Germany decided last October to begin forcing the refugees
to go home unless they volunteered to go. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
