<DOCNO> XIE19970328.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cuba Still Willing to Take Peruvian Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Cuba reiterated its willingness
today to receive the Peruvian rebels who are holding 72 hostages
inside the Japanese ambassador's residence in Lima.
</P>
<P>
A deal is reportedly in the works in which the Tupac Amaru
rebels would free the hostages in exchange for asylum in Cuba and
a multimillion dollar payoff.
</P>
<P>
There had been no change in the position of Cuba since the
talks between Cuban President Fidel Castro and his Peruvian
counterpart Alberto Fujimori early this month, Cuban Foreign
Ministry spokeswoman Marianela Ferriol said.
</P>
<P>
Havana awaited an agreement, as well as an official request
from the Guarantors Commission, to receive the Tupac Amaru
members, said the spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
The Lima hostage crisis hit the 100-day mark today. The
previous Latin America's hostage holding record was 61 days when
the Dominican Embassy was seized in 1980. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
