<HEADLINE> Injuries Ruin England World Cup Plans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 27 (Xinhua) -- England will field a virtual
second-string team when they face Mexico in a friendly at Wembley
on Saturday after an unprecedented injury crisis deprived coach
Glenn Hoddle of no fewer than 17 players.
</P>
<P>
Hoddle acknowledged that the match will now be of little help
in England's preparations for the World Cup assignment against
Georgia on April 30.
</P>
<P>
The list of players unavailable amounts to almost two full
England teams and includes strikers Alan Shearer, Les Ferdinand,
Nick Barmby and goalkeepers David Seaman and Ian Walker.
</P>
<P>
The midfielders ruled out are Paul Gascoigne, Steve Stone, Paul
Merson, Andy Hinchcliffe, Darren Anderton, David Beckham and Matt
Le Tissier.
</P>
<P>
The defence has been hit by injuries to Gary Neville, Tony
Adams, Sol Campbell, Gary Pallister and Dominic Matteo.
</P>
<P>
By contrast, Mexico will field a full-strength side as they bid
for a hat-trick of victories over England.
</P>
<P>
Mexico's key players include striker Carlos Hermosillo, who has
seven goals in his last 11 appearances and is regarded as a
modern-day Hugo Sanchez. 
</P>
</TEXT>
