<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil to Import Huge Amount of Crude </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Brazil will import 6.3
billion U.S. dollars worth of crude oil and byproducts this year,
Joel Renno, president of the Brazilian state oil company,
Petrobras, said here today.
</P>
<P>
National oil output grew 20 percent from January 1995 to
December 1996, rising from 750,000 to 900,000 barrels a day, Renno
said.
</P>
<P>
Domestic oil output met only 53 percent of domestic demand,
which had registered a yearly increase of 6 percent during the
last two years, said Renno.
</P>
<P>
To reduce crude imports, the Brazilian government adopted
several measures to increase production, setting a goal of 1.2
million barrels a day in 1998 and 1.5 million barrels at the end
of the decade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
