<HEADLINE> Zairean Govt, Rebels Reaffirm Principle of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOME, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Zaire's government and rebel
delegates today reaffirmed the principle of ceasefire and peace
talks, according to the communique released here today by the
special summit of the Organization of African Unity (OAU).
</P>
<P>
The communique, read by Togolese Foreign Minister Pierre Panou
at the end of a consultation held after the OAU special summit,
said the agreement was reached under the mediation of OAU, the
Untied Nations and African regional leaders.
</P>
<P>
Camerounian President Paul Biya who is also the current OAU
chairman, Nigerian President Sani Abacha who is also chairman of
the Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS), United
Nations Secretary-General Koffi Annan, OAU/U.N. special envoy on
the Zairean crisis Mohamed Sahnoun, as well as delegates of the
two warring parties, attended another consultation as most of the
30 African leaders left for home after the special OAU summit.
</P>
<P>
The date of the start of peace talks and ceasefire would be
announced simultaneously in Lome, Kinshasa and Goma after the
delegates of Zaire's warring parties report to their leaders back
home, said the communique.
</P>
<P>
The Lome summit is the first peace effort participated in by
both sides of Zaire's warring sides as rebels, led by Laurent
Kabila, won one victory after another and has occupied about one
third of the territory of the Africa's third largest country
since they started the civil war at the end of last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
