<HEADLINE> China Wants No More Confrontation over Human </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Qiao Shi, chairman of the Standing
Committee of the National People's Congress (NPC) of China, said
here today that China does not wish to have more confrontation
with certain Western countries over human rights.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with French President Jacques Chirac, Qiao
thanked France for supporting China over the issue of human
rights.
</P>
<P>
"We don't wish to have more confrontation over human rights.
Certain Western countries proposed anti-Chinese resolutions at
international human rights conferences, which have badly hurt the
feeling of the Chinese people, as well as the relations between
China and these countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
Qiao said that China does not oppose having dialogue over human
rights, but the outcome of such dialogue should not be the
precondition for stopping confrontation between China and certain
Western countries over human rights.
</P>
<P>
On the perspective of China's joining the two United Nations
human rights conventions, Qiao said that China is studying the
issue with an active attitude.
</P>
<P>
He said that Chinese law experts are looking into the clauses
of the two conventions to compare them with Chinese laws. 
</P>
