<HEADLINE> Mozambique's Ban on Sea Cucumber Fails </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Mozambique's ban on fishing of
sea cucumber in the sea waters of the southern province of
Inhambane has achieved little results, Rodolfo Macassa, director
of the provincial fishing administration, disclosed here today.
</P>
<P>
Macassa was quoted by the Mozambican News Agency as saying the
ban, which was meant for protection of the rear species of sea
cucumber, has been seriously violated by the local people.
</P>
<P>
"The ban failed to put a halt to the trend of sea cucumber
extinction in the region," he said.
</P>
<P>
Macassa said though the government has stopped issuing
licenses to fishermen, but supervision of the ban was very weak
due to poor manpower with only three supervisors covering over
the 700 km seashore.
</P>
<P>
Fishing and export capacity of sea cucumber, which is both
edible and for the use of shoe-making and rubber industry, were
not known, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
