<HEADLINE> Stock Prices Plunge as Interest Rates Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Prices plunged on Wall Street
today as the long-term interest rates jumping over 7 percent, and
strong economic data incited fears that the Federal Reserve would
again push interest rates higher.
</P>
<P>
Stock prices were mixed in early trading, but after the
Treasury's 30-year bond yielding broke through 7 percent -- a
level feared by stock and bond investors -- the Dow Jones
industrial average fell steadily and sharply. In late trading it
was down more than 216 points before recovering some ground.
</P>
<P>
The Dow fell 140.11 points to 6,740.59 at the closing. It was
the blue chip index's eighth-largest point drop.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by more than 3 to 1 on
the New York Stock Exchange, with NYSE volume totaled 475.93
million shares as against 487.33 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index fell 16.62 to 773.88.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE's composite index fell 7.94 to 407.43.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index fell 19.58 to 1,249.50, and the
American Stock Exchange composite index dropped 5.17 to 577.90.
</P>
<P>
The markets were nervous about another interest rate increase.
</P>
<P>
Market analysts said today's trading was also affected by
technical factors including end-of-the-quarter portfolio
adjustments. And they noted the market's plunge came on relatively
light volume because many traders left early for a three-day
weekend. The stock market will be closed for Good Friday.
</P>
<P>
Early today, the government issued strong home sales and
jobless claims reports, a day after it reported a surge in durable
goods orders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
