<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Shocked by 39 People Mass Suicide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 27 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
said today that "it's heart-breaking, it's sickening, it's
shocking," when he expressed his unease over the apparent mass
suicide involving 39 people at a southern Californian mansion.
</P>
<P>
"I think it's important that we get as many facts as we can
about this and try to determine what in fact motivated those
people," Clinton told reporters at a White House briefing.
</P>
<P>
He also said it should be determined "what all of us can do to
make sure that there aren't other people thinking in that same way
out there in our country, that aren's so isolated that they can
create a world for themselves that may justify that kind of
thing."
</P>
<P>
U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno earlier said the Federal
Bureau of Investigation (FBI) was working with state and local law
enforcement officials to handle the matter.
</P>
<P>
The 39 people were found dead Wednesday in a million-dollar
mansion at Rancho Santo Fe in northern San Diego County. They were
dressed in matching black pants and dark tennis shoes, lying in
apparent peace on their backs, arms at their sides, each covered
across the face and chest with a triangular shroud of purple
cloth, reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
San Diego Sheriff's deputies said that there was no gunshot
wounds, no knife holes in anybody, no signs of struggle or trauma.
Investigators believe the group, at the age of 18 to 24, died in a
mass suicide.
</P>
<P>
Local reports said that the group sent a farewell videotape to
a former member, announcing their plans and may have timed their
deaths to the approach of the Hale-Bopp comet.
</P>
<P>
The members believed it was time to "shed their containers,"
perhaps to rendezvous with a UFO they believed was traveling
behind the Hale-Bopp comet, which can be observed from Earth in
these days, a source close to a former member said.
</P>
<P>
The reports said a former member of the group received two
videotapes by mail Tuesday evening. One video was of the group's
leader and the other contained each member's taped farewells.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a website, apparently designed by Higher Source, a
thriving business designing Web pages and apparently centered at
the mansion where the "suicide" occurred, described the group's
desire to leave Earth and rendezvous with a spaceship behind the
Hale-Bopp comet.
</P>
<P>
"The joy is that our Older Member in the Evolutionary Level
above human (the `Kingdom of Heaven') has made it clear to us that
Hale-Bopp's approach is the `marker' we've been waiting for....
Our 22 years of classroom here on planet Earth is finally coming
to conclusion _ `graduation' from the Human Evolutionary Level. We
are happily prepared to leave `this world' and go with Ti's crew,"
the Heaven's Gate Website reads.
</P>
<P>
However, there was no information on the Heaven's Gate Website
that connected it to the Higher Source group. There is a separate
Website under the Higher Source name. The Heaven's Gate Website
said suicide was unacceptable for people who were not part of the
group but was an acceptable way for members to ascend to a higher
level of life, a report said.
</P>
<P>
Investigators searched the house and refrigerated vans from the
coroner's office stood by. One of the vans, which is capable of
holding 20 bodies, pulled away from the home about 5:15 a.m. and
arrived at the morgue in San Diego an hour and a half later.
</P>
<P>
If it was confirmed, it was another biggest mass suicide in the
country in little more than four years. On April 19, 1993, Branch
Davidian leader David Koresh and 80 followers died by fire or
gunfire, six hours after the FBI started filling their cult
compound near Waco, Texas, with tear gas. The government called
the deaths a mass suicide after a 51-day armed standoff. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970328.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Chief Recommends Extension of Haiti Force </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 27 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan on Thursday recommended to the Security Council that
the mandate for a 762-member U.N. force in Haiti be extended until
31 July, 1997.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council extended the U.N. Support Mission in Haiti
(UNSMIH) until 31 May 1997. In doing so, it was the council's
understanding that, under the recommendation of the
secretary-general, its mandate could be extended for the final
time until 31 July 1997. The force were sent to Haiti mainly to
help the government form a professional national police force.
</P>
<P>
In his report, Annan drew attention to a letter by Haitian
President Preval last November, which said it would take between 8
to 12 months for the Haitian police force to be able to ensure a
secure and stable environment.
</P>
<P>
"It is clear from the present report that UNSMIH can make a
further contribution to that goal and to the objective of
resolution 1086, which affirms the importance of a professional,
self-sustaining, fully functioning national police force of
adequate size and structure, able to conduct the full spectrum of
police functions, to the consolidation of democracy and
revitalization of Haiti's system of justice," he said.
</P>
<P>
After consultation with Haitian government and several other
concerned countries, Annan said he came to the conclusion that in
order to ensure the continued institutional development of the
Haitian national police force, the mandate of UNSMIH should be
extended for the final time until 31 July 1997.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
