<HEADLINE> Clinton Endorses Mammography Advice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 27 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton is
endorsing a National Cancer Institute recommendation that women in
their 40s get regular mammograms.
</P>
<P>
Speaking shortly after the NCI issued its revised
recommendations, Clinton said on Thursday that the long-debated
advisory from his chief cancer research and education agency
provided "clear, consistent guidance" for women.
</P>
<P>
He issued a series of recommendations urging that health care
plans serving women in their 40s fully cover annual mammograms.
The recommendations propose that Congress change Medicare and
Medicaid rules to fund the cost.
</P>
<P>
Clinton also announced plans for a national public education
campaign to provide women with information on the subject.
</P>
<P>
The NCI said Thursday it was recommending mammography every one
to two years for women with no special risks of breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
Some 44,000 U.S. women died of breast cancer last year,
including 4, 700 women in their 40s, and an NCI advisory panel of
experts concluded that regular screening would reduce deaths from
breast cancer by nearly 17 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
